<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Leaving Belgrade with No breakthrough on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke made no breakthrough on Kosovo peace after his talks
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and will leave
Belgrade in a few hours, the White House said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There's been no breakthrough in these talks," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke has met Milosevic twice in Belgrade, but could not
force the Yugoslav president to agree that NATO troops police
peace in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"I've been informed that unless there is some dramatic change
in President Milosevic's position, that Ambassador Holbrooke
plans to leave Belgrade in the next few hours," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton was briefing a group of members of
Congress from both parties on the situation in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
