<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Presses for Removal of Border Obstacles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has called for the removal of immigration
formalities and conditionalities that hinder cross border trade.
</P>
<P>
COMESA Secretary General Erastus Mwencha said immigration
formalities force people engaged in cross border trade to evade
normal border posts and routes.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha was speaking at the first cross-border traders
education seminar held Tuesday in Lusaka, Zambia's capital.
</P>
<P>
In some cases, he said, cross border traders are involved in
collusive fraud with officers manning borders and roadblocks. He
said these practices have robbed governments some revenue.
</P>
<P>
Mwecha also called on governments to recognize the cross
border traders association so as to create transparency in cross
border trade.
</P>
<P>
He said in most countries, cross border traders, despite being
 essential to economic growth, are still viewed as smugglers.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha also disclosed that Zambia's total informal cross
border export to the Democratic Republic of Congo, Tanzania and
Zimbabwe amounted to 28.6 million kwacha (15,000 U.S. dollars)
between September 1997 and 1998 in exports.
</P>
<P>
He further stressed the need for the currencies of member
states to be easily convertible into one another to create a free
trade area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
