<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Meets Italian Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin met
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema here Tuesday to exchange
views on bilateral ties and international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the Sino-Italian relationship was good and the
two countries had made great progress in cooperation in every
field.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that mutual respect and benefit were indispensable
for countries to get along with each other. "This is why Sino-
Italian ties have remained good," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president said that both sides should strengthen
dialogue and cooperation in bilateral and international matters.
"This not only conforms with the interest of the two peoples, but
is also conducive to China-Europe and Asia-Europe cooperation and
peace and development in the world."
</P>
<P>
D'Alema welcomed Jiang warmly on behalf of himself and the
Italian government. He said that Jiang's visit was another
important event in bilateral relations following Italian President
Oscar Luigi Scalfaro's visit to China last June.
</P>
<P>
The Italian premier said that China had made tremendous
progress during the past 20 years and was playing an ever more
important role in world politics and economics.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that Italy was an important trade partner of China
in Europe. Generally speaking, bilateral economic and trade
cooperation had grown rapidly.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that both countries would continue to
make joint efforts in economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema agreed with Jiang's views on bilateral relations,
saying that Italy was willing to further its relations with China
in politics, trade and economy, technology and science, culture
and other fields.
</P>
<P>
The Italian premier also praised China for its important role
in stabilizing regional and world financial situations.
</P>
<P>
He said that Italy supported China's bid to join the World
Trade Organization and would make active efforts in helping China
enter the world trade body.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the Asian financial crisis, which began in 1997,
adversely affected the world economy and China adopted a highly
responsible attitude by not devaluating its currency, contributing
to stabilizing the Asian and world economies and easing the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
China was willing to join with other countries to strive for a
stable international financial market and a just and reasonable
international economic order, the Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that he hoped Italy would continue with efforts to
push the European Union to show greater flexibility in negotiating
China's bid for WTO membership so that substantial progress would
be made as early as possible to enable China to join the world
trade body.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday morning, Jiang also met with some Italian
businessmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
