<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Well Fire in India's Western Offshore Spreads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A fire raging at an offshore
gas well in western India has engulfed more wells and the owner of
the wells has decided to "kill" them, reports reaching here said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A shallow seismic survey in and around the burning area had
been ordered at a cost of 1 million U.S. dollars to help locate
the "hot spot" and identify the location of "relief" well, the
Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from Mumbai.
</P>
<P>
Uncontrolled leakage of gas from a well caught fire on March 12
and at least three more wells on the platform have been engulfed
in the fire.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen three of them burning and may be another one will
also be engulfed," PTI said, quoting Mark Mazella, a senior well
control specialist from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mazella, who arrived at the scene 10 days ago to help
extinguish the fire, told a press conference in Mumbai that one of
the tasks to be performed involved "killing" of the burning wells
to stop the flow of gas.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the fire control operations since March 12
including expenses on multi-purpose support vehicles, helicopters
and experts fees amounted to 3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
A survey vessel is expected to reach the area in the first week
of April and it would start generating information a couple of
days subsequently, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the fire is likely to take two months to be
extinguished and therefore the loss in terms of gas production is
expected to be sizable.
</P>
<P>
Oil and Natural Gas Corporation, owner of the wells, lost about
1.6 million cubic meters of gas per day, or 3 percent of the total
gas production in offshore western India, about 1,500 kilometers
southwest of here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holyfield Insists Fight Result against Lewis was Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Evander Holyfield insisted on
Tuesday that heavyweight unification bout between him and Lennox
Lewis was fair.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday's fight ended in a draw but most observers
concluded World Boxing Council champion Lewis had outpointed
Holyfield, the World Boxing Association and International Boxing
Federation title holder.
</P>
<P>
American Holyfield, speaking for the first time since studying
a tape of the fight, said the result had been fair.
</P>
<P>
"I truly believe that people have been deceived, with all the
punch stats, the commentary, what the commentators were saying,"
he told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
"The fact is that Lennox fought a smart fight, fought a good
fight, but we both in general didn't do enough to declare a bid to
be undisputed champion..."
</P>
<P>
"We have bad days at the office but we have to get over the bad
days...It wasn't a great day for me but I got through that day and
I thank God for that."
</P>
<P>
Particular interest focused on U.S. judge Eugenia Williams,who
scored the fight 115-113 in favour of Holyfield. A New York grand
jury is investigating whether or not the judges took illegal
payments, according to investigative sources.
</P>
<P>
But Holyfield said that even had Williams made errors, it would
have made little difference to the result.
</P>
<P>
"If you look at her scores you can see there's only one round
where she could have been wrong," he said, adding that even then,
Lewis had only dominated it for 15 to 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"Even if she was off one round it would have made the(overall
score) 115-114," he said.
</P>
<P>
"When you look at the fight for what it really was, all the
judges had me winning the eighth, ninth, 10th and 11th rounds --
that's four rounds. Everyone had me winning the third. And one had
me winning the fourth.
</P>
<P>
"If you look at the first round, it's not as though he really
won the first round. He did win the second round, but the first
round was questionable."
</P>
<P>
The two boxers will fight again for the undisputed world
heavyweight title in September at a venue yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to that. I've signed a contract already...and I
hope we go ahead and settle this thing,"Holyfield said, expressing
a preference for Las Vegas over London as the venue for the fight.
</P>
<P>
"But it really doesn't make a difference to me -- I can win
either way," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
