<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Explosion Wounds Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A man was slightly injured on
Tuesday in an explosion at a scrapyard in the town of
Castlewellan, a Northern Irish police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"There was an explosion in a street in Castlewellan, in County
Down, at 12:09 p.m. (1209 GMT). A man has been injured, not
believed seriously. Army experts have been called to the scene,"
said the spokesman for the Royal Ulster Constabulary.
</P>
<P>
He added British army bomb disposal experts were on the scene.
</P>
<P>
The blast in Castlewellan, about 55 km south of Belfast,
occurred as a Belfast court was meeting to rule on a British
government move to block the imminent release of four Irish
Republican Army prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Northern Ireland are increasing as the province's
peace process runs deeper into the mire. Last week a prominent
Catholic human rights lawyer was murdered by Protestant
extremists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
