<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Sets Terms For Kosovo Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Tuesday that Yugoslav troops in Kosovo must be brought
down to agreed level for peace to be achieved in that region.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the House of Commons, Blair called on Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to return his soldiers to barracks
and withdraw the heavy weapons from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Curbing Serb oppression in Kosovo is the basic objectives of
NATO forces, the Prime Minister told the parliament members.
</P>
<P>
He alleged that a NATO-led ground force would have to be
deployed in Kosovo to implement peace there.
</P>
<P>
"Britain stands ready with our NATO allies to take military
action," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
His statement comes as NATO continues preparations for possible
air strikes against Yugoslavia following the failure of crisis
talks between U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and the Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is reported to prepare to leave Belgrade within
hours.
</P>
<P>
"To walk away (from Kosovo) now would destroy NATO's
credibility," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister warned that the potential consequences of
military action were "serious".
</P>
<P>
But he said "the consequences of not acting are more serious."
</P>
<P>
After his Kosovo statement, Blair is due to fly to Berlin for a
three-day EU summit.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the prime minister's official spokesman said there was
no reason why UK forces could not go into action while Blair was
out of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
