<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says no Breakthrough in Kosovo Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke achieved no breakthrough on Kosovo peaces, the White
House said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There's been no breakthrough in these talks," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke has met Slobodan Milosevic twice in Belgrade, one on
Monday night and the other on Tuesday morning, but could not force
the Yugoslav president to agree that NATO troops police peace in
the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton was briefed by his foreign policy
team on the talks between Holbrooke and Milosevic, and then
briefed a group of members of Congress from both parties on the
situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said Holbrooke laid out a "compelling and clear case
for why President Milosevic should change his position, both in
the interest of the Serbs and the Kosovar Albanians and the
region. But I can't tell you this morning that there is a solid
expectation right now that he will change."
</P>
<P>
"On the one hand he laid out the positive case for reaching a
political settlement in Kosovo. On the other hand he laid out
what the other path could be, which is swift and substantial
NATO action," Lockhart added.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its NATO allies have warned Belgrade
through the crisis that failure to comply with NATO's demand
for Western presence in Kosovo will be punished with NATO
military strikes which could begin quickly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
