<HEADLINE> Cyprus: Air Strikes Will not Solve Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government is
monitoring developments in Kosovo and does not believe that air
strikes will bring about a solution, Cyprus' government spokesman
Costas Serezis said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus' Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides is in
constant touch with the country's ambassador to Belgrade, who is
in contact with Cypriot nationals staying in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Serezis said Cypriots would be advised to leave Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Javier Solana, secretary-general of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, Tuesday night directed NATO Supreme Commander
General Wesley Clark to begin military intervention in the Kosovo
crisis with air operations against military targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
His decision came after United States Balkans envoy Richard
Holbrooke failed to persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
to accept an ultimatum to avoid NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke asked Milosevic to call back his troops in Kosovo and
sign a peace deal with ethnic Albanians which would allow NATO
forces to station in this Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav government rejected the demand, and instead
proposed for major changes of the peace deal, which would give
autonomy to ethnic Albanians who make up 90 percent of the
population in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
