<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Differ Over Strikes in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the 15 European Union (
EU) member states were still split on Wednesday over NATO military
action against Yugoslavia although they were poised to issue a
strongly-worded statement in a bid to put utmost and final
pressure on the Yugoslav government to sign the Kosovo peace deal.
</P>
<P>
At the EU summit meeting in Berlin, diplomatic sources
confirmed that at least four countries remained neutral and
certain countries were not in favor of launching military actions
over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The EU statement was meant to be a final appeal to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to accept the Rambouillet peace
accord, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
But British officials here said they had no expectations that
Milosevic would fall into line.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who is
attending the EU summit, said NATO forces were ready to launch air
strikes against Yugoslavia over Kosovo and the attack would begin
"in the not too distant future".
</P>
<P>
But Blair could not clarify when the strike would begin and how
long it would take. "Now we are left with no other alternative
than to take military action," he said. "We have to see it
through all the way."
</P>
<P>
British government sources also said that there was "a huge
degree of unity" on the NATO course of action.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on Tuesday authorized NATO
troops to take military action against Yugoslavia. He told
reporters at the Brussels-based NATO headquarters that he made the
authorization because the last-ditch effort by U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke in Belgrade failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
