<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Soccer Players Jailed Over Match-Fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) - Three Hong Kong international
soccer players were jailed for 22 months each on Wednesday over
match-fixing.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Lok Kar-win, 25, Chan Chi-keung, 28, and Wai Kwan-lung,
22, were also each fined 30,000 HK dollars (about 3,870 U.S.
dollars), the Independent Commission Against Corruption (ICAC)
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
They were also deprived of their registered status in Hong Kong
after the Hong Kong Football Association Ltd. (HKFA Ltd.) was
informed that the trio were sentenced to jail. HKFA Ltd. will
discuss the possibility of a life-time ban on the three players
next week.
</P>
<P>
The three men were accused of conspiring with the team's
striker Chan Tsz-kong to win bets by ensuring Hong Kong was beaten
by two goals by Thailand in a World Cup qualifier in 1997. Hong
Kong lost 2-0. 
</P>
