<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: NATO Steps in Europe's Powder Keg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The threat of imminent NATO air
strikes against Yugoslavia is hanging over the European Union
summit in the German capital, Berlin, starting on Wednesday, after
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on Tuesday authorized the use
of military force to resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
After Solana's announcement, both NATO leaders and the leaders
of European countries repeatedly said that NATO had been "left
with no other alternative than to take military action" and that
the military action could be stopped if Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic would pull back his army from Kosovo and sign a
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
But it sounds more precise to say that NATO itself has chosen
to take the current "no alternative" position.
</P>
<P>
After the Cold War ended with the collapse of NATO's historical
adversary, the Warsaw Pact Group, NATO was left as the world's
largest military alliance with no enemy.
</P>
<P>
Russia, and even analysts in the West, have cast doubts on the
need for NATO's existence. The military alliance has itself also
begun to seek reasons for its existence and enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the former Yugoslavia has offered such a
chance and excuse for NATO.
</P>
<P>
For historical reasons, Yugoslavia is a nation composed of
multiple ethnic groups and there exists comprehensive rivalry and
hostilities among the different ethnic communities.
</P>
<P>
The current instability and rivalry in the Serbia's troubled
southern province of Kosovo gave NATO, which used to claim that
its role was to keep stability and security in the Atlantic areas
and Europe, an excuse to have a hand in that region.
</P>
<P>
Adding that Yugoslavia used to be a friend of the former Soviet
Union and currently Russia, NATO's hypothetical enemy, NATO was
eager to poke its nose there to show its strength and squeeze out
Russia's influence.
</P>
<P>
That's the reason why NATO rushed to meddle in the dispute in
Kosovo, a very clearly internal affair of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
From the very beginning, NATO and the West stood on the side of
the Kosovo Albanians. The Kosovo peace plan initiated by the West
requires "substantial autonomy" for Kosovo and says Yugoslavia
should "invite" NATO forces to Kosovo to "monitor the
implementation of peace" -- very harsh elements the Yugoslav
government clearly could not accept in consideration of its
integrity and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Although NATO's aim was to force the Yugoslav government to
bend to its pressure, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, an "
iron-fisted" man as Western media call him, is certainly not easy
to deal with. Even after NATO's repeated military threats and "
final attempts at a diplomatic solution", he refused to sell his
country's sovereignty by signing the peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
So, NATO was now "left with no other alternative than to take
military action".
</P>
<P>
But it will not be easy for NATO to take the military action.
</P>
<P>
As British media have said, the Balkan region is a powder keg
with a short fuse. World War I started there in the early years
of this century. During World War II, Yugoslavia, occupied by
German Nazis, was the most active area in the anti-Nazi guerrilla
wars.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair said on Wednesday that NATO
knew the risks of taking action.
</P>
<P>
It is time now for NATO to decide how deep it wants to be
pulled into that "powder keg".
</P>
<P>
But no matter what kind of action it takes against Yugoslavia,
NATO will have to face the risk of putting itself in a very
dangerous position. As some analysts have pointed out, if not
handled cautiously, Kosovo might turn out to be "Vietnam in Europe
".
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, NATO officials announced that it would probably
launch the first air strikes against Serbia "during the day or
Wednesday evening at the latest."
</P>
<P>
But what would happen after the strike? If Milosevic still
rejects the peace plan, would NATO send ground troops into Kosovo?
What would happen if NATO soldiers died in Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
NATO officials and leaders in European countries will have to
answer these questions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Backs Yugoslavia's Peaceful Efforts Over Kosovo: Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 24 (Xinhua) - Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov on Wednesday reaffirmed strong support to Serbia and the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in efforts to reach a peaceful
political solution in Kosovo, Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone call to Milosevic, Primakov "expressed Russia's
determined stand against outside threats of force which represent
a great danger with unforeseeable consequences", Tanjug said,
quoting a foreign ministry statement.
</P>
<P>
"President Milosevic has underlined Serbia's and Yugoslavia's
commitment to a peaceful political resolution guaranteeing
equality for all national communities, to working out clear
principles of Kosovo autonomy with respect for the sovereignty and
integrity of Serbia and Yugoslavia," Tanjug said,
</P>
<P>
It said Yugoslavia appreciated the "principled stand and
support" of Primakov and Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who have
strongly opposed NATO action against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug said Milosevic stressed that Russian support for
Yugoslav efforts to protect its sovereignty under NATO threats had
"great importance for the political process and the legitimate
national and state interests of Serbia and Yugoslavia and for the
future of relations in Europe and the world, particularly for the
future of relations in the region of southeast Europe".
</P>
<P>
"It was agreed that in the current situation (Yugoslavia and
Russia) should continue constant contacts and consultations."
</P>
</TEXT>
