<HEADLINE> India Investigates Alleged U.S. Plane Intrusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- India is to finalize a report
on the alleged intrusion of an American plane into Indian airspace
within a week, Minister of Civil Aviation Ananth Kumar said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to part with piecemeal information. Air traffic
security is an important matter and is being examined closely,"
Kumar told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The statement was in contradiction with reports here Tuesday
which said the U.S.-registered plane was cleared of charge of
taking photographs over "restricted areas" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The cameras in the aircraft were reportedly not capable of
taking pictures at night and not working when found inside the
plane.
</P>
<P>
J. C. A. Cooper, a British pilot, and his female navigator, J.
M. Kondgaj, were detained on charge of spying in Ahmedabad, 915
kilometers southwest of here, on March 17 and have been under
investigation ever since.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said the only mistake made by the crew members
of the twin-engine turboprop private survey plane was that they
did not mention anything about the cameras they had kept in the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The crew reportedly told their interrogators that they took off
from Calcutta for Karachi on March 16 and landed at Ahmedabad for
refueling.
</P>
<P>
They said the director general of Indian civil aviation had
cleared them when they landed a day earlier in Calcutta, about
1,900 kilometers east of Ahmadabad.
</P>
<P>
They were on their way to Dubai via Karachi when they were
detained at Ahmedabad on charges of over-flying Indian airspace
without permission and for not possessing proper immigration
papers.  Cooper holds a British passport while Kondgaj has an
Australian one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
