<P>
The country had deployed a large force on the border with
Kosovo and all government departments had entered a state of war,
Majko said.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government held two emergency meetings after NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana on Tuesday night authorized NATO
air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address following the government's second
emergency meeting, Majko said the country's sovereignty was "holy"
and the government was doing its utmost to work out concrete
measures to deal with the worst scenario in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Albania fears that NATO air strikes could trigger attacks from
Yugoslavia against Albania, since the country backs the ethnic
Albanians in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Majko said Albania had received assurances of NATO protection
in a letter Wednesday from Solana.
</P>
<P>
Solana said Albania's security was of "direct and material
concern" to NATO. He promised that NATO would seriously deal with
any attack from Yugoslavia against Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
