<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Strengthened Coop with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Deputy President Christon
Tembo expressed his hope here Wednesday that his country will
enhance and expand cooperation with China especially in mining
sector.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Zhang Wule, visiting Chinese director
of State Nonferrous Metals Industry Administration, Tembo
described the relations between the two countries as "very warm",
saying the two sides have enjoyed very long and friendly relations
since Zambia's independence in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years the ties have been strengthened and the two
sides have had a lot of cooperation programs such as the
1,860-kilometer Tanzanian- Zambian railway built by China over 20
years ago and the Zambia-China Mulungushi Textiles Joint Venture,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in mining industry is a new one, he said, hoping
that after China starts operation in Chambish mine it bought last
year, the cooperation will be expanded.
</P>
<P>
The deputy president pledged that his country will be ready to
help in China's endeavor in the mine in northern Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Investment from western countries has been the sole foreign
capital in Zambia's mines, he said. China, a developing country,
has put its investment in Zambia's mine development now, he said
</P>
<P>
Zhang told Tembo that China is able to run the mine well and
achieve good economic returns.
</P>
<P>
He called for more cooperations like joint exploration and
production in the mine industry with China providing expertise and
Zambia offering recourses for the benefit of both sides.
</P>
<P>
Zhang and his party also met with Zambian Commerce, Trade and
Industry Minister David Mpamba and Energy Minister Ben Mwila,
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang arrived here Tuesday for a week-long visit. 
</P>
