<HEADLINE> Russia Calls for Resumption of Peace Talks on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov Thursday warned that Russia would withdraw from the arms
embargo against Yugoslavia if NATO carried out its threatened air
strikes resulting from the failed Kosovo peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting to discuss the latest situation in
Kosovo, Ivanov told reporters that the situation was extremely
tense and the NATO would probably take military action against
Yugoslavia within hours.
</P>
<P>
The negotiation process on the Kosovo issue should be continued
as the issue could only be resolved through political dialogue,
Ivanov said. The sooner the talks resumed, the faster a solution
could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's meeting was also attended by Russian Defense
Minister Igor Dmitriyevich Sergeyev and officials from the General
Staff of Russia's armed forces and the Foreign Intelligence
Service.
</P>
<P>
Russia believed that use of force against Yugoslavia would be
counter-productive and NATO could not achieve its aim by launching
military strikes, which would result in deaths of civilians, an
exodus of refugees and a deterioration of the situation, Ivanov
said.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade should acknowledge its responsibility in finding a
solution to the Kosovo issue and sign the political agreement
which was ironed out recently in Paris, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister said that it was a compromise to
sign the agreement and the purpose of doing so was to protect the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia while
respecting the rights of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A compromise should be made to pave the way for continuing the
peace talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov added Moscow would seriously consider the possibility of
unilaterally withdrawing from the arms embargo imposed on
Yugoslavia if the NATO air strikes went ahead. 
</P>
