<HEADLINE> Last Cambodian Refugees Return From Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The last group of Cambodian
refugees in Thailand returned Wednesday with the help of the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and the Cambodian Red
Cross.
</P>
<P>
About 850 refugees, the last of more than 80,000 people who
fled the country after fighting broke out in 1997, returned from
the Huay Cheung camp in Thailand's Surin Province across the
border from O'Smach.
</P>
<P>
Uy Sam Ath, director of disaster management for the Cambodian
Red Cross, told reporters that some of the refugees hope to return
to their native places in Mondulkiri, Ratanakiri and Stung Treng
provinces and some will go to the area around the northern
Cambodian town of Samraong.
</P>
<P>
Three camps were set up in Thailand after the Cambodian
refugees fled there in 1997 because of factional fighting and in
April last year when government troops pushed into rebel-held
territory in northern Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The fighting ended late last year with the surrender of Khmer
Rouge members and the reintegration of the resistance forces loyal
to Prince Norodon Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
Huay Cheung is the last of the three major refugee camps in
Thailand and the other two were closed last week and in early
February respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
