<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Eases Rule on Property Ownership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Thai spouses and children of
foreigners can, from now on, own land and properties under
amendments to the 1941 Land Act, the Interior Ministry announced
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Interior Minister Sanan
Kachornprasart approved the amendments by signing an amended
ministerial regulation on Tuesday, according to an Interior
Ministry statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendments, a Thai legally married to a foreigner
will be able to buy or receive a transfer of land if the money is
his or her personal property and not jointly acquired by the
couple during marriage.
</P>
<P>
If a foreign spouse, however, does not confirm that the money
is the sole property of the Thai, or says the money is jointly
owned, a minister in charge of the Land Department can veto the
purchase request.
</P>
<P>
The amended provision also applies to a Thai national who is
not legally married to a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
A Thai married to a foreigner, regardless of the legality of
their marriage, can also receive land given as personal and not
jointly owned property.
</P>
<P>
A Thai divorced from a foreigner and a mixed-blood child
holding Thai nationality can also acquire land through legal
transactions, according to the amendments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
