<HEADLINE> Clinton Prepares for Imminent Attack on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- With members of his foreign
policy team with him at the White House early Wednesday morning, U.
S. President Bill Clinton was preparing the nation for an imminent
attack on Yugoslav targets.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and allied warships and bombers stood ready on Wednesday
to deliver a "swift and severe" blow to Yugoslavia, starting with
a U.S.-led barrage of sea-and-air-launched cruise missiles that
would target Yugoslav air defenses and open the way to a larger-
scale bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on Tuesday for the nation to support military
action against Yugoslavia, saying U.S. diplomatic efforts had
reached a dead end and it must "take a stand now".
</P>
<P>
"If we don't do it now, we will have to do it later," he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on Tuesday evening gave
NATO's top commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the formal go-
ahead.
</P>
<P>
"No alternative is open but to take military action," Solana
said at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed on Wednesday on ABC's Good Morning America, Solana
said: "Up to now we have not heard of any change in the behavior
of President Slobodan Milosevic.... We are going to continue with
the decision taken yesterday."
</P>
<P>
An opening volley of cruise missiles would be fired from four U.
S. Navy ships and two submarines in the Adriatic, along with one
British submarine, plus U.S. Air Force B-52 bombers flying from a
base in England.
</P>
<P>
Air Force F-117 stealth fighter-bombers based in Italy are also
likely to be involved in first attacks against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
As NATO strikes appeared all but inevitable, Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov registered his opposition by canceling a
scheduled visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
Attempting to patch up differences with Russia, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright spoke by telephone for more than half an
hour with her Russian counterpart Igor Ivanov, according to State
Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Albright told Ivanov that she hoped the United States and
Russia could find a way "to deal with the situation and continue
to work in other ways".
</P>
<P>
She also conferred twice by telephone with Solana and talked
separately with the foreign ministers of France, Britain and
Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
