<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Law Lords Rule No Immunity for Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Britain's highest court ruled on
Wednesday that former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet is not
immune from prosecution, opening the way for a hearing on his
extradition to Spain.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet's arrest in Britain was lawful, the seven-man panel of
Law Lords announced in the House of Lords, the upper chamber of
the British parliament.
</P>
<P>
The ruling, made by a vote of six to one, said Pinochet enjoyed
no immunity from prosecution for human rights abuses during his
1973 to 1990 rule simply because he was a former head of state.
</P>
<P>
But the Law Lords said he was responsible only to charges of
crimes committed after 1988, the date when Britain incorporated
the United Nations convention on torture into law.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, was arrested in London last October on a warrant
from Spain. A Spanish judge accused him of being responsible for
the deaths and disappearances of 3,000 people and requested his
trial in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet has been under house arrest in a rented mansion near
London since his detention.
</P>
<P>
Last November, another Law Lords panel decided that he had no
immunity from prosecution and should face extradition proceedings.
But that ruling was set aside because one of the judges was
alleged of having strong links with the human rights body, Amnesty
International.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's decision again paved the way for proceedings to
decide whether Pinochet can be extradited to Spain.
</P>
<P>
Earlier during the day, a Chilean air force plane landed at an
air base near London, ready to take Pinochet back home in case the
Law Lords ruled in favor of the retired general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
