<HEADLINE> World TB Day Alerts Public to Danger of Tuberculosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculosis is still a major
disease in the world including Hong Kong, said a Hong Kong senior
health official at a ceremony marking the World Tuberculosis Day
held here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Paul Saw, Hong Kong's acting director of health, said the
number of tuberculosis cases reported here still stands at around
7,000 cases per year.
</P>
<P>
"We have to continue to be alerted and not to loosen our anti-
TB work, " added Dr. Saw.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there were various types of high quality
anti-tuberculosis services in Hong Kong and it is hoped that the
disease could be eliminated through the joint efforts of the Hong
Kong government and the citizens together with international
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
There were 7,673 TB cases reported in 1998, compared with 7,072
and 6,501 reported in 1997 and 1996 respectively in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization and the International Union
Against Tuberculosis and Lung Diseases have declared March 24 as
the World Tuberculosis Day.
</P>
<P>
This year's slogan in Hong Kong is "Hong Kong is our home, anti-
TB work will depend on all our own." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
