<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7th Letter to Help Thailand Spur Economy: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Finance Minister
Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said here Wednesday that the country's
seventh letter of intent to the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
will help jump start the economy next month.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the letter, which was passed by the
cabinet Tuesday, Tarrin said it will serve as the government's
economic policy framework through June, when the next review of
economic performance is scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Under the seventh letter to the IMF, the government would be
allowed to run a 6-percent budget deficit of the country's gross
domestic product (GDP) to eventually achieve the targeted
1-percent real economic growth rate this year.
</P>
<P>
The government will also try to achieve a low-level 2.5-percent
inflation and maintain 32 billion to 34 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said most of the approved deficit would be financed by
foreign loans, including those from Japan's Miyazawa Plan and the
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund, the Manila-based Asian
Development Bank and the World Bank. The rest of about 1 percent
would come from new government spending programs and tax cuts
included in the new economic stimulus package.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government is expected to announce the new economic
stimulus package on March 30, focusing on job creation programs
and boosting of the social safety net.
</P>
<P>
It would also direct progress toward legal and structural
reforms, namely strengthening the bankruptcy and foreclosure
systems and liberalizing investment in key sectors, the finance
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The seventh letter of intent is expected to be approved by the
IMF Executive Board on April 7 before a new IMF standby credit of
490 million dollars is released to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
So far, Thailand has received 12.46 billion dollars in
financial assistance from the IMF-initiated 17.2 billion dollar
rescue package since the economic crisis broke out in mid-1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
