<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States and its NATO allies on Tuesday ordered
warships and strike aircraft to commence bombardment of Yugoslav
military targets -- as early as Wednesday -- after President
Slobodan Milosevic spurned a final demand to halt his offensive
against ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
-- With NATO airstrikes imminent, the Yugoslav government has
put the country on a war footing, declaring a state of emergency
and calling up thousands of military reservists following
president Milosevic's defiant rejection of a U.S. envoy's eleventh-
hour bid to win agreement on a peace plan for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Initial NATO bombings of Serbia will be broader and more
punishing than originally envisioned, going after 60 targets
instead of delivering short, sharp strikes, European and American
officials said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, en route to
Washington for seeking financial aid, ordered his pilot to turn
his airliner around and return to Moscow after received a
telephone call from U.S. Vice President Al Gore who informed
Primakov the United States and NATO were preparing to launch
airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The oil ministers from the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries signed on Tuesday a widely anticipated pact to
cut global oil output to put up oil prices.
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton administration, trying to strike a balance
between protectionism and free trade as it confronts increased
imports of foreign steel, signaled support for a move in Congress
to bolster enforcement of U.S. trade laws. 
</P>
