<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Company Donates Artificial Legs to Disabled Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A disabled man with only one leg
has been given the chance of re-starting his life thanks to a Sino-
Canadian medicare program which provides artificial limbs free of
charge.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhongyin, a 29-year-old man living in a poor village in
southwest China's Yunnan Province, lost his left leg in an
accident in August last year and has been dependent on his family
every since.
</P>
<P>
Now, he said, with the new "leg" he can even return to his work
as a farmer.
</P>
<P>
The Carolwood Corporation Canaola of Canada first started its
program of providing free limbs to Chinese people in 1997 and so
far 105 people have benefited. There are some 9 million people
disabled in such a way in China and 700,000 of them need
operations or false limbs.
</P>
<P>
And in a month's time a further 199 disabled people like Zhang
will receive the same kind of help in the province.
</P>
<P>
The program has funding of 400,000 yuan from the Carolwood Corp.
and 200,000 yuan from the local government and was inaugurated on
March 18. Since then 16 people have received artificial limbs.
</P>
<P>
They are all part of the lower leg, which are cheap and
technically simple to make, compared with other artificial limbs,
according to experts. Each artificial leg costs about 400 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Melissa Bailey, an official of the Canadian company, said that
the company will continue its efforts to cooperate with China in
setting up training centers in underdeveloped inland provinces of
Guizhou and Gansu next year to train local technicians in fitting
and looking after artificial limbs.
</P>
<P>
Xu Xiaoming, an official of the China Disabled Persons'
Federation, said that China is speeding up the work to establish
artificial limb centers in every province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
