<HEADLINE> Train Accident Kills 30 in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan passenger train heading
for the country's biggest port Mombasa derailed Wednesday
morning, killing at least 30 people.
</P>
<P>
Police confirmed 30 dead but expected the toll to rise.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said at least 23 foreign tourists were critically
injured, including Americans, Germans and Canadians.
</P>
<P>
The overnight train, which is convenient for tourists
travelling from the capital Nairobi to Mombasa in the south,
derailed near a junction about 300 kilometers southeast of
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Survivors of the accident said the train suddenly jumped off
the tracks when going at a high speed, flipping one car upside
down and at least four others askew.
</P>
<P>
A Kenyan air force aircraft rescued 23 seriously injured
foreigners to Nairobi's Wilson Airport. Then they were rushed to
major hospitals in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's police, army and National Disaster Committee were
leading the rescue operation with help from the Kenyan Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi-Mombasa train service became more popular after the
El Nino rains destroyed the road in late 1997. Rehabilitation
of the road is still under way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
