<HEADLINE> Britain Backs Prodi as EU Executive Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, March 24 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
reaffirmed here Wednesday he favors former Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi as the next president of the European Commission, the
executive branch of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"What I have always said is that we must have a candidate of
high caliber who is a reformer because Europe needs reform. Mr
Prodi would certainly fit that bill, but let us wait and see what
candidates emerge," said Blair, who is here attending an
extraordinary EU leaders meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair told the BBC that it was not yet clear whether
the two-day Berlin summit would reach a decision on filling the
post.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to wait and see what candidates are available,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister also rejected speculations that he
had made a deal with Italy to support Prodi in return for Italy's
support for Britain retaining its three-billion-US-dollar rebate
from the European Union.
</P>
<P>
All of the EU's 14 other members want a change of Britain's
special rebate deal which has been in place since 1984. EU leaders
at the summit are expected to discuss this issue. 
