<HEADLINE> HK Government Supports Electronic Transactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) Government has decided to take the
lead in establishing a local public key infrastructure and a root
certification authority in Hong Kong to facilitate e-business.
</P>
<P>
The fast development of the Internet in the past few years has
provided new opportunities for businesses, such as lower-cost and
flexible sales, reduced unproductive inventory and more efficient
and focused service, HKSAR Secretary for Information Technology
and Broadcasting K C Kwong told a dinner meeting of the Business
Week Chief Information Officer (CIO) Forum here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, for a business to feel comfortable about
using the Internet in transactions with its suppliers and
customers, it needs to be sure of the identity of the other party
to the transaction and that any agreements made electronically are
binding.
</P>
<P>
The solution is for a safe and secure environment to be created
for the conduct of electronic commerce, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the Hongkong Post has been tasked
with the establishment of the public key infrastructure and its
certification service should be up and running by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
In parallel, Kwong said, the SAR Government is preparing
legislation to prescribe that electronic records will have the
same legal status as their paper-based counterparts.
</P>
<P>
It will also provide for the voluntary registration of
certification authorities and the legal recognition of digital
signatures accompanied by certificates issued by these registered
authorities, he added.
</P>
<P>
To encourage the community to engage in electronic commerce,
Kwong said, the SAR Government will take the lead in providing
government services on line over the Internet under the Electronic
Service Delivery scheme (ESD).
</P>
<P>
The purpose is to improve the delivery of government services
on one hand and to drive the development of electronic commerce on
the other, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This will in turn spur the development of more electronic
commerce, in both variety and volume, in Hong Kong," he said,
noting that the first phase of ESD would be implemented by the
latter half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, more than 120 top information officers from
around the world attended the CIO Forum to discuss how best
information technology (IT) can be used to navigate and regenerate
businesses through the current economic downturn in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two-day forum, entitled "Leading Change: Business Alignment
Through Information Technology," addresses issues such as e-
business, the year 2000 problem, insourcing and outsourcing and
supply-chain management.
</P>
<P>
Forum organizers said the CIOs are playing a far more important
role today than before and this forum comes at a time when IT
development is at the top of the agenda for Asia's governments and
companies alike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
