<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Accuses Eritrea of Repatriating 2,500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has accused the
Eritrean government of recently repatriating over 2,500 Ethiopians
without first notifying the International Committee of the Red
Cross (ICRC), which in turn was unable to inform Ethiopia of the
pending repatriation.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Tuesday, Ethiopian government
spokesperson Selome Taddesse said the Ethiopian government was
"incapable of making the necessary preparations for their
arrival."
</P>
<P>
The repatriated were "thus dumped at the border town of Humera
-- a precarious area during this time of war -- without access to
such basic needs as food and shelter," she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she announced Tuesday that the fighting continued
between Ethiopian and Eritrean forces in the vicinity of Merer
River, near Shembeko.
</P>
<P>
The western front of the border war near the Shembeko started
last Friday. Fighting at central front of Zalambessa-Egela which
started on March 14, has ceased.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of African unity (OAU) has described the
border war between the two Horn of Africa neighbors as "a matter
of profound regret".
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim said Monday at the
just-ended 69th Session of OAU Council of Ministers that despite
efforts by OAU, "the war resumed with greater intensity... with
its attendant loss of life and destruction and its complicating
consequences for the peace process."
</P>
<P>
He called on both countries to end fighting immediately and
implement the OAU peace proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
