<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African FMs Demand UNITA Leader Cease Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The African foreign ministers
 Wednesday demanded that Angola's rebel UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi
 "immediately cease military activities and surrender all armament
in the spirit of national reconciliation."
</P>
<P>
The 69th Ordinary Session of the Council of Ministers of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) has adopted a "decision on
Angola", reiterating that Savimbi and his military wing have not
honored their obligations as provided for in the 1994 Lusaka
Protocol, in the United Nations Security Council and OAU
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The council said the above-mentioned fact is "the root cause
underlying the resumption of war and the impasse in the
implementation of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
It strongly supports the decision made by the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) summit held in Mauritius in September
1998 at which the chairman of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) was declared a war criminal, and an
appeal was made for the strengthening of measures with a view to
fully isolate him.
</P>
<P>
The council supports the efforts made by the Angolan government
in a bid to put an end to the war and promote democracy and
national reconciliation in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The "decision on Angola", which was the only one adopted by the
council on African conflict situation, appeals to OAU member
states "to strictly apply the package of sanctions adopted by the
U.N. Security Council, particularly those imposed on the
travelling of UNITA leaders and decision-makers as well as on the
means of communication."
</P>
<P>
The decision further appeals to the international community to
provide economic and humanitarian aid required for the
reconstruction of Angola, particularly the rehabilitation of the
infrastructure destroyed by the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
