<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Producers Warn of Collapse of Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- West African Portland Cement
Company (WAPCO) of Nigeria has warned of imminent collapse of
local cement industry as imported cement has increased
tremendously.
</P>
<P>
Records compiled by the WAPCO from eight cement factories in
the country showed that local cement production fell by more than
30 percent while import of the commodity rose by 130 percent over
the past nine years.
</P>
<P>
According to the records, while 3.03 million tons of cement
were produced in 1990 in the west African country, the figure
dropped to 2.2 million tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, imported cement increased from 905,595
tons to 2. 15 million tons, the records showed.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Makoju, managing director of the WAPCO, was quoted by
Wednesday's Daily Times as saying that unless the trend arrested,
Nigeria would depend entirely on import for its cement
requirements in the next five year.
</P>
<P>
He described the situation as a sad development, saying the
product is fundamental for infrastructural development and the
nation has comparative advantage because of the 100 percent local
raw material availability.
</P>
<P>
Makoju attributed the situation to the previous governments'
policies which tend to favor active promotion of cement import,
adding the major problems confronting Nigeria's cement industry
include persistent shortage of energy and the flood of cheap
cement imports from South East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The South East Asian countries, he said, recently devalued
their currencies, and could price their manufactured goods very
low in dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he noted, their modern high-volume, low-cost
cement plants could produce cement at manufacturing cost of about
20 dollars per ton while local factories are producing at an
average manufacturing cost of about 62 dollars per ton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
