<HEADLINE> Sweden Asks for Switch of Site of Table Tennis Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSLO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Sweden would not compete at the
world table tennis championships, planned to be hosted in
Yugoslavian capital Belgrade, unless the event is moved to another
country, a Swedish table tennis official has said.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Table Tennis Association chief Ulf Loennqvist told
Swedish newspapers on Tuesday that his organization had made a
written request to the International Table Tennis Federation (ITTF)
that the event be switched to another country.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish table tennis body made the decision out of
consideration of the political and security situations in
Yugoslavia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Loennqvist said if the ITTF insisted on holding the event in
Belgrade, it would become a regional event with much smaller scale.
</P>
<P>
The official added that Sweden would also not send a delegation
to the ITTF Congress if it was held there.
</P>
<P>
"We are still waiting for the final decision from ITTF before
considering how to act. If the event is held in Belgrade, it will
eventually become something like an Asian championships,"
Loennqvist was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, national table tennis associations
in the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, Austria, France, Denmark,
Norway, Finland, England and Italy have decided not to participate
in the championships in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The ITTF will decide on Thursday how to cope with the situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
