<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges NATO Not To Take Military Action Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China is urging NATO to cancel
its decision to launch military strikes against Yugoslavia
immediately, Vice Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi said here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Yang repeated the statement in two separate meetings with
Yugoslavia's Ambassador to China Slobodan Unkovic and U.S. Charge
d'affaires William C. McCahill.
</P>
<P>
He laid out China's stance on the Kosovo issue by saying, "The
Chinese government opposes the use of force or the threat of the
use of force in international affairs, and opposes interference in
other nation's internal affairs no matter what the excuse or by
what means, and opposes any random action that circumvents the U.N.
Security Council."
</P>
<P>
China is asking all those involved to continue all efforts to
reach a political settlement in the Kosovo issue by peaceful means,
he went on to say.
</P>
<P>
Yang reiterated the Chinese government's stance in insisting
that the Kosovo issue is Yugoslavia's internal affair and a "
problem that can only be solved through dialogue based on a
respect of the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia
and an ensuring of the lawful rights of all ethnic groups in
Kosovo." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Expand Judicial Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Over 1,000 work groups will be
dispatched to local procuratorates to rate the professional
integrity of Chinese prosecutors as part of an effort to expand
the internal restructuring of the nation's judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Procurator-General Han Zhubin announced today that the Supreme
People's Procuratorate (SPP) will also introduce a three-year
training and education program for all chief prosecutors in local
procuratorates.
</P>
<P>
Han said the goal of the measures is to "consolidate the
results" of the judicial restructuring campaign initiated last
year, and root black sheep tarnishing the image of the nation's
hundreds of thousands of prosecutors."
</P>
<P>
Han made the remarks during a national teleconference focusing
the opinions and criticism deputies to the National People's
Congress tabled concerning the work report he presented during the
annual NPC Session held earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
He said NPC deputies not only tabled a number of "insightful"
opinions, criticism and suggestions on last year's restructuring
and the SPP's work, but also reaffirmed its achievements.
</P>
<P>
"We must take them seriously," said Han.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to hold chief prosecutors fully responsible for
ensuring the professional integrity of subordinates.
</P>
<P>
Han said that reform to the current prosecution system will be
key to preventing and eradicating judicial corruption.
</P>
<P>
Han also listed the following aspects of reform: strengthening
the general public's supervision of prosecutorial activities;
assigning chief prosecutors responsibility for certain cases;
instituting an expert consultation mechanisms; improving the work
of procuratorate prosecution committees; streamlining internal
structures; and restructuring the personnel system.
</P>
<P>
"We must ensure the comprehensive enforcement of reform
measures and I expect to see concrete results during 1999," said
Han.
</P>
<P>
He instructed prosecutors to intensify the work against
corruption and focus on what he called "major and important cases"
related to crimes committed by high-ranking officials and cases
involving large sums of illicit money.
</P>
<P>
He added that prosecutors must prove their cases based on hard
evidence, due process and discretion in order to ensure
convictions stand the test of time.
</P>
<P>
"Any violations of the law or discipline by prosecutors will
not be tolerated," said Han. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
