<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Faction Fighting, Banditry Attacks Kill 8 Somalis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 24 (Xinhua) -- At least eight people were
killed and as many as 16 others were wounded in three separate and
terrible incidents in Mogadishu Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A serious shooting took place between rival militiamen loyal to
faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed at Sisi area of North Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses told reporters Wednesday that four people were
killed on the spot while seven others were wounded. All victims
were innocent civilians, many of whom were having tea in the
shades of the trees before the tea shops, they added.
</P>
<P>
Another even more serious shooting took place in the busy
Manapolio market of North Mogadishu late Tuesday.  At least three
people including two women were killed during the exchange of fire
while nine others were wounded near the market place.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said the deceased women were on board a public
transport minibus passing through the market and caught in the
cross fire.
</P>
<P>
The rival militiamen whom the people said were from the same
subclan of Harti-Abgal loyal to Ali Mahdi had fled the area after
each side had faced an unexpected resistance form the other side.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the attacks are not known.
</P>
<P>
However, militiamen close to those fighting against the militia
 commander Abdullahi Dhahan said that they had something to do
with the banditry activity which occurred last week when a vehicle
was looted.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Dhahan and his militiamen had pursued bandits
who looted the vehicle to Jowhar town, some 90 kilometers north of
Mogadishu, and killed one of them before taking the looted vehicle
back forcefully from the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Annoyed bandits from the same subclan of those who looted the
vehicle had ambushed Dhahan and his men at Sisi area of North
Mogadishu in retaliation to his attack on the bandits.
</P>
<P>
Another man, an elderly Sheikh, was killed in a separate
banditry attack near Bakara market of South Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitnesses, the Sheikh was killed and some money
he was carrying with him was taken away after three armed young
men had attacked him on his way to taking a bus to his house in
Wardhigley District of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The reason is said to have been one of the day-light banditry
activities in Mogadishu where there's no single authority dealing,
or planning to deal, with the lawlessness which persisted in the
Somali capital in the past eight years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
