<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Muslim Leader on Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The leader of Indonesia's
largest Muslim group said here on Wednesday that he believed the
June elections in his country would be open and fair.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the Institute of Defense and Strategic Studies
of Singapore, Abdurrahman Wahid, leader of the Nahdlatul Ulama
(NU), said the June 7 elections would be open and fair based on
observations of four key institutions on the military and
civilians.
</P>
<P>
"The second thing is that participating parties would like to
see a fair election, otherwise the punishment would be too high,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The elections would be good, the monitoring would be good as
well," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
On difficulties facing Indonesia in the coming elections, Wahid
said where the money will come from is the biggest headache for
Indonesia. But he expressed the belief that Indonesia would manage
to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Wahid also outlined his political and economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Wahid said he is for a new form of politics and a new form of
institutions of state.
</P>
<P>
"We have to give provinces full autonomy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Governors and district leaders would not be appointed by
Jakarta and instead be elected by the population," he added,
saying Jakarta now has too much a say in the internal affairs of
the provinces.
</P>
<P>
He also vowed to maintain unity by changing the revenue sharing
scheme between Jakarta and provinces.
</P>
<P>
Wahid expressed the hope that the law would be observed and
equal treatment would be given to people from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
He also said he is for the freedom of expression,
responsibility of government to the people and a supreme court to
be independent of the executive.
</P>
<P>
The Soeharto and Habibie governments depend too much on import,
he said. "We want to build another economy that is oriented to the
use of our own resources and looks to the outside only if
necessary."
</P>
<P>
"We want to keep profit to ourselves," he stressed. "If our
policy is right, we could manage to get better." 
</P>
</TEXT>
