<HEADLINE> Albanian Cabinet Meets to Discuss Situation over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli
Majko on Wednesday called an emergency cabinet meeting in the
small hours to discuss what further steps to take in regards to
the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, which began at 02:30 local time, Majko, in the
presence of reporters, read a solidarity letter sent to him by
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, after he had given the go-
ahead for the alliance to launch air raids against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to stress that the Alliance will very seriously
consider any attack by the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia against
your country. The alliance has repeatedly made clear that the
security of each of the NATO members is inseparably linked with
that of all the nations of the Partnership. Your security is a
concrete and direct concern of the Alliance," said the letter.
</P>
<P>
The meeting then continued behind doors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Second Infantry Division in Kukes prefecture
neighboring Kosovo has been put on high alert, not only along the
border, but also in deeper regions.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the division, Azem Perllaku, told the Albanian
Telegraph Agency (ATA) that a part of the forces is on the alert
to intervene if needed, while the division's commanding staff are
in constant touch with the government and the army general staff.
</P>
<P>
Perllaku said that this unit has been reinforced considerably.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tuesday night the mobile forces of the division
carried out another alert drill and that the staff of the division
are working out all possible variants to cope with a military
aggression against Albania. 
</P>
