<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Kenya Names New Anti-Graft Chief to Meet IMF Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The president said in a statement that Ringera would be
seconded to the authority by the Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Almost all the Kenyan national newspapers reported this
appointment on their front pages and hailed this move as an
important action in the fighting against corruption.
</P>
<P>
The appointment comes in the wake of a police crackdown on
vehicle smuggling, fake security documents, such as dollars, bank
notes, logbooks, death and birth certificates.
</P>
<P>
Ringera has been the solicitor-general since 1997, and taught
in the Faculty of Law at the University of Nairobi for more than
10 years and was a practising advocate before his elevation to a
judge.
</P>
<P>
Ringera takes over at the helm of the authority, replacing its
first director John Harun Mwau who served the body for seven
months before being suspended and subsequently facing of a
tribunal appointed by President Moi to look into whether he was
capable and competent to head the organization.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said earlier that they were considering
offering the post to a foreign national, but business leaders
opposed a foreign appointment on the grounds that there were more
suitable kenyan candidates.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's appoint brings to a close speculations that a
foreigner was geared to take the post.
</P>
<P>
It is also believed that the appointment is aimed at paving the
way for the resumption of aid talks with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The appointment of the anti-graft chief has been one of the
conditionality imposed by the IMF and the World Bank for the
resumption of aid talks. The other demanded by the two
institutions is fiscal discipline in the financial sector,
including the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said early this month that Kenya must name a director
and deputy director of KACA before the talks on the loan agreement
could restart.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended its Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facilities
- a three-year loan agreement totaling 205 million U.S. dollars
to Kenya in July, 1997, due to grave graft and poor governance,
which pushed Kenya's economic structural reform into a dire
predicament.
</P>
<P>
The IMF sent a six-member technical team to Kenya a month ago
for the resumption of the suspended aid.
</P>
<P>
After two-week investigations, the team concluded that Kenya
had met three of four conditions imposed by the IMF, and the only
one remained was the appointment of a director of the KACA.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission also said that the Kenyan government had made
 considerable progress in strengthening fiscal and monetary
policies in 1998.
</P>
<P>
With the appointment of the KACA director, the Kenyan
government showed its sincerity and greater efforts for tackling
the graft issue and paved the way for its talks with IMF.
</P>
<P>
However, the ball is now rolling to the IMF side. The Kenyan
government and people are to wait and see when will the IMF
realize its promise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Remains Secure as Regional Service Center: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Harvard economist Jeffery Sachs
said here Wednesday that Hong Kong's position as a regional
service center will not be easily taken away though the economy
is now struggling in a recession.
</P>
<P>
Professor Sachs told a press conference: "Hong Kong and
Singapore will continue to have unique advantages that won't
easily be taken away."
</P>
<P>
The two places remain secure in such regional functions as
financial and information technology centers, said Sachs, who
predicted that no other Asian cities or cities out of Asia can
take their places in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
He said their competitive edge depends on underlying strength
and growth in other parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Although Hong Kong is in continuing deflation, it remains one
of the richest, freest and well-managed economies in the world,
said the Harvard economist.
</P>
<P>
Sachs is here as a keynote speaker at the three-day Credit
Suisse First Boston second Asian investment conference, which
started Wednesday. He delivered an address entitled "Major
Challenges in Asia's Economic Recovery." 
</P>
</TEXT>
