<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Prop of Local Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Shanhai Pass in the city of
Qinhuangdao in China's Hebei Province hosted 1.75 million tourists
and earned 280 million yuan from tourism in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Tourism dominated the local service trade which generated 620
million yuan in earnings in the past year, contributing to 60
percent of this seaside summer resort's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Shanhai Pass is situated between the Yanshan Mountains and the
Bohai Bay, between north and northeast China. It is the eastern
end of the Ming Section of the Great Wall, the most famous part of
the Great Wall, which was built some 350 years ago. Since 1985
when the late senior Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping called on the
whole nation to love and renovate the Great Wall, the city
government has spent more than 60 million yuan on improving this
tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization has put the Badaling Section of the Great Wall, also
a popular tourist destination north of Beijing, on the World
Heritage List.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges NATO Not To Take Military Action Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China is urging NATO to cancel
its decision to launch military strikes against Yugoslavia
immediately, Vice Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi said here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Yang repeated the statement in two separate meetings with
Yugoslavia's Ambassador to China Slobodan Unkovic and U.S. Charge
d'affaires William C. McCahill.
</P>
<P>
He laid out China's stance on the Kosovo issue by saying, "The
Chinese government opposes the use of force or the threat of the
use of force in international affairs, and opposes interference in
other nation's internal affairs no matter what the excuse or by
what means, and opposes any random action that circumvents the U.N.
Security Council."
</P>
<P>
China is asking all those involved to continue all efforts to
reach a political settlement in the Kosovo issue by peaceful means,
he went on to say.
</P>
<P>
Yang reiterated the Chinese government's stance in insisting
that the Kosovo issue is Yugoslavia's internal affair and a "
problem that can only be solved through dialogue based on a
respect of the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia
and an ensuring of the lawful rights of the ethnic Albanians."
</P>
</TEXT>
