<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Govt Officials Barred From Holding Campaigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's General Election
Committee (KPU) Wednesday decided to bar all government officials,
from central to village administration levels, including
ministers, from participating in campaigns during the June general
election.
</P>
<P>
The decision is taken based on the outcome of a vote among
members of the KPU.
</P>
<P>
"As many as 46 voted to agree to bar government officials from
campaigning and 22 votes disagree. It means KPU's decision is to
bar them from participating in campaigns until the end of the
general election," KPU chairman Rudini told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said if any party tries to violate the committee's decision,
there will be a sanction against them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, member of the KPU from the ruling Golkar party
Mahadi Sinambela said that although they regret the final
decision, the party will have to accept it.
</P>
<P>
"I think there is no problem for Golkar to hold a campaign
without a minister, as there are many Golkar cadres who have the
ability to campaign," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Golkar party leader Marzuki Darusman said it will
reconsider its political support to the cabinet if President B.J.
Habibie agrees with the ban.
</P>
<P>
Most government ministers are Golkar members.
</P>
<P>
"If President Habibie wants to be 'reelected,' he has to lobby
members of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR). Golkar itself
will assess how far the MPR can support President Habibie's
nomination. This matter will very likely influence Golkar party's
presidential nomination," Darusman said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 48 political parties will contest the June 7 general
election. The multi-party elections will elect a new House of
Representatives, whose members will be part of the 700-strong MPR,
the nation's highest legislative body, which will select the next
president.
</P>
<P>
Under former president Soeharto, who was forced to step down on
May 21 last year, only three parties were allowed to contest
elections. They were the Golkar party, the United Development
Party and the Indonesian Democratic Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
