<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Not to Be Directly Involved in NATO Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime Minister Orban
Viktor said on Wednesday that his country will not participate
directly in NATO's threatened military actions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
So far, there has been no indication that NATO's air strikes
will jeopardize Hungary's security, Orban said in a radio address
while commenting on the situation in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Even if such a situation occurs, Hungary will still be safe, as
it is already a NATO member and will be under the umbrella of
NATO's defense system, Orban said.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister said, the possibility for solving
the Kovoso crisis through peaceful means still exists, although it
is diminishing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hungarian Foreign Minister Martonyi Janos told a
local newspaper on Tuesday that his country has always hoped that
the Kosovo issue could be solved through a political means. Even
if NATO resorts to force, its military actions should be limited
ones.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian leaders have said that the country would not
participate directly in NATO military strikes. If required by NATO,
Hungary will send small technical and medical teams to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Hungarian parliament has passed a bill to
allow NATO to use its airspace, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on Tuesday ordered
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, saying all efforts for a negotiated
solution to the Kosovo crisis had failed.
</P>
<P>
"All efforts to achieve a negotiated, political solution to
the Kosovo crisis having failed, no alternative is open but to
take military action," Solana told reporters at the headquarters
of the Western alliance in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Serbs have recently refused to sign an agreement with
the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, saying the agreement violated
Yugoslavia's sovereignty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
