<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Council of Ministers' Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The 69th Ordinary Session of
the Council of Ministers of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) ended here Wednesday morning after adopting many decisions
and one regulation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing ceremony, Jean Ping, chairman of the
current session of Council of Ministers and Foreign Minister of
Gabon, said that the two-day deliberation not only completed all
financial and administrative issues on the agenda, but also
discussed political issues of the continent.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that African foreign ministers would meet again in
Algeria at next session which will be held in July this year.
</P>
<P>
The current session of the OAU Council of Ministers was mainly
devoted to the consideration of financial and administrative
matters of the organization.
</P>
<P>
It has adopted a total of six decisions on these issues,
expressing "serious concern about the reversed trend in settling
outstanding financial obligations by some member states especially
those which continue to accumulate arrears of contributions over
several years."
</P>
<P>
The council of ministers appealed "to all member states with
outstanding contributions to settle regularly and timely their
financial obligations so as to enable the organization meet its
increasing challenges and discharge its normal functions."
</P>
<P>
The African foreign ministers also adopted some other decisions
on the OAU convention on the prevention and control of terrorism,
on the status of OAU treaties, on OAU/European Union summit and on
the reconstructions of the (OAU) General Secretariat, and etc.
</P>
<P>
The council also decided that any member states failing to
honor the rescheduling plan will automatically fall under
sanctions provided by the financial rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The regulation adopted at the meeting ruled that the OAU
General Secretariat should propose to the third ordinary session
of Economic and Social Commission (ECOSOC) of the African Economic
Community clear-cut measures to set up a consultative forum of
African parliamentarians, as a prelude to the creation of a
Pan-African Parliament provided for under the treaty on
establishing the African Economic Community.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also said that the OAU General Secretariat
should take urgent measures to establish the African Energy
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The council also made some rules on African countries'
effective participation in the negotiations with EU, and those
with the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The current Session of the OAU Council of Ministers Opened here
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
