<HEADLINE> Too Early to Talk About Response to NATO Strike: Russian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 24 (Xinhua) -- It is now too early to talk about
Moscow's responding moves to NATO's possible use of force against
Yugoslavia, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said on Wednesday,
when taking a question from the press.
</P>
<P>
He said the power to decide on any move belongs to President
Boris Yeltsin in his capacity of Russia's supreme commander and
diplomatic chief.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here said Ivanov urged public figures in Russia
not to rush to commenting on the issue as what they say would not
necessarily be put into practice.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister stressed that there was no reason
whatsoever to carry out military actions against Yugoslavia; there
has been no decision from the UN Security Council nor any law
which allows NATO to resort to force.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov noted that he had telephone talks late Tuesday with some
of his Western counterparts, including U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, warning them of possible serious consequences
of such inconsiderate military actions.
</P>
<P>
"After using force, any sensible person would ask what to do
next, and no one can answer this question," he said.
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
