<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Genocide Suspect Open to Trial by Any </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Bernard Ntuyahaga, a
Rwandan genocide suspect released by the International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) last week, is open to trial by any
state, ICTR registrar Agwu Ukiwe Okali said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Okali said that Ntuyahaga can be re-arrested in the future even
by the ICTR on the basis of other charges or by any government or
authority with a legitimate interest, said an ICTR press release
reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal's decision to release him as a consequence of the
prosecutor dropping charges has not made him any better off than
before he was arrested, Okali said.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga, 47, a Major in the former Rwandan Armed Forces,
surrendered himself to the Tribunal on July 10, 1998 and was
indicted on September 29 with one count, namely crimes against
humanity (murder).
</P>
<P>
He was allegedly responsible for disarming and arresting the 10
Belgian soldiers who were sent to escort Rwandan Prime Minister
Agathe Uwilingiyimana before they were killed on April 7, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR Tribunal last Thursday granted the prosecution leave to
withdraw its indictment against Ntuyahaga and set him free.
</P>
<P>
But Ntuyahaga has since preferred to stay in the United Nations
custody for fear of being extradited to Rwanda or Belgium which
have both sought his trial in their courts.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed the tribunal's ruling for his acquittal.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the extradition requests to Tanzania by Belgium
and Rwanda, the registrar said that is not a question for the
Tribunal, but one between the states concerned.
</P>
<P>
"The Tribunal has no preference for any country's interests,
and indeed, has denied Belgium's request for Ntuyahaga to be
handed over to that country or any other country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Okali said that Ntuyahaga has been a free person since last
Thursday, but he has remained at his own request in the United
Nations Detention Facility (UNDF) on the outskirts of Tanzania's
north town of Arusha where the ICTR is based.
</P>
<P>
On a question as to whether the release of Ntuyahaga has
created a dangerous precedent by encouraging states to request for
trying tribunal suspects in national courts, the registrar said
that any such danger has been forestalled by the tribunal's clear
position that it does not have jurisdiction to do so and therefore
could not do so.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga's release is a result of the bid by his prosecutor,
Othman Chande who argued that the withdrawal will promote the
exercise of concurrent jurisdiction by a state as contained in
article 8 of the statute of the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the prosecutor's motion followed a request by the
Belgian government which has tried to transfer the trial of
Ntuyahaga to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Established on November 8, 1994 by the United Nations Security
Council, the ICTR has the mandate to try persons suspected to be
responsible for genocide and other serious violations of the
international humanitarian law committed in the territory of
Rwanda between January 1 and December 31, 1994.
</P>
<P>
It also has the mandate to try Rwandan citizens responsible for
such violations committed in the territory of neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR has so far issued 28 indictments against 45
individuals and a total of 36 indicted individuals are still in
custody, 35 of them in the UNDF in Arusha and one is detained in
Texas of the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
