<HEADLINE> Scholars Encourage Promoting Creative Spirit of Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- "Parents should nurture the
creative spirit of their children", according to Child
Psychologist Chen Huichang
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Wednesday seminar sponsored by the overseas
edition of People's Daily, Chen, a professor with the Child
Psychology Institute at Beijing Normal University, quoted an
article in the US-based Wall Street Journal as saying that Chinese
people constitute one of the world's wisest groups. However, the
article noted that members of the Chinese nationality rarely win a
Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the reason to the fact that "various restraining
elements in China's education system" stifle the originality of
Chinese children.
</P>
<P>
Chen urged parents to refrain from attempts to "mold" children
according to their own ideals, but instead should help them
realize their ideals.
</P>
<P>
Bai Chunli, vice president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences,
noted that "one characteristic of the knowledge-based economy era
is to absorb new knowledge".
</P>
<P>
He stressed that individuals adept at acquiring knowledge will
be able to withstand the increasingly fierce competition.
</P>
<P>
Continuing education has emerged as the mainstream in the age
of knowledge. Experts in the fields of education, science and
technology should help people "acquire new knowledge" after
completing their formal education, said Bai.
</P>
<P>
Song Chaodi, president of the Clever Software (Group) Co. (CSC),
China's largest education software producer, stressed that the
information society requires people to re-consider the question of
how to study and the question of for what one should study.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 scholars and experts attending the seminar discussed
approaches for using science and technology to revitalize China.
</P>
</TEXT>
