<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Works for Debt Relief Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has taken
major steps in its efforts for negotiations with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) on debt relief from its creditors, This Day
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In January, Nigeria drew up a Staff Monitored Program (SMP) and
 submitted the program to the IMF, and last month the Nigerian
government forwarded a memorandum on economic and financial
policies to the Bretton Wood institution.
</P>
<P>
In the memorandum, the Nigerian government explained in details
the policies it plans to implement to enable it to qualify for
discussion on the Medium Term Economic Strategy (MTS) which is the
precondition for negotiations on debt relief.
</P>
<P>
Last week, IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus, who was on a
three- day visit to Nigeria, said that the IMF board will meet in
July to assess how well Nigeria has implemented the SMP.
</P>
<P>
According to Camdessus, it is the quality of progress made by
the Nigerian government in the implementation of the SMP that will
determine if it can proceed to the next stage of MTS.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the SMP which is purely home-grown by Nigeria, the MTS
has the full involvement of the IMF by making available necessary
soft financial facilities.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum covers seven key policy areas: fiscal policy,
social expenditure and poverty alleviation; monetary and exchange
rate policy; domestic deregulation and privatization; trade and
exchange liberation; governance and institution building and
external debt management.
</P>
<P>
The major plank of its fiscal policy, according to the
memorandum, will be fiscal adjustment which aims to minimize the
adverse effects of the oil price slump and the disruption in
Nigeria's crude oil production.
</P>
<P>
These factors put together would reduce budgetary revenue in
1999 by an estimated 2.4 billion U.S. dollars which amounts to 6.8
percent of Nigeria's gross domestic product (GDP) in the
assumption that the average world oil price would be nine dollars
per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government said that its priority will be to
maintain macro-economic stability while allowing interest and
exchange rates to reflect market forces.
</P>
<P>
On the external debt management, the Nigerian government is
determined to normalize relations with the Paris Club by sending
reconciliatory missions to the creditor countries to establish
authenticity of all figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
