<HEADLINE> Observers Say Consumer Spending In China Will Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The sluggish domestic demand is
expected to change when state policies to stimulate the economy
begin to take effect in the second quarter of next year, the State
Internal Trade Bureau (SITB) says.
</P>
<P>
China's markets are growing and the buyer's market is not
likely to change in the short run, market observers say.
</P>
<P>
Increased input in infrastructure to stimulate demand and
increased production of cement, steel, and rolled steel are
expected to increase more profits than for consumer goods. China
passed financial policies last year to boost consumer spending and
some of them have had some effect.
</P>
<P>
As macro-economic policies take effect, consumer spending is
expected to gradually pick up, which will help avoid further
inflation and price rise and will encourage enterprises to improve
competitiveness to survive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
