<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
passed on any further attempt to push further into record
territory Wednesday, giving the 3,000 point threshold a wide berth
after Wall Street stocks fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index went nowhere near its
record-breaking performance of Tuesday when it spiked through
3,000 points for the first time, instead slumping 21.9 points to
close at 2,965.7.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index rose seven points to 1,033.9 while the
all industrials index shed 52.1 points to 5,330.2.
</P>
<P>
Australia's biggest industrial company BHP, which reports its
third quarter results on Friday, climbed 40.2 cents to 13.46
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Fellow leader Rio Tinto was 30.2 cents stronger at 22.314
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector also fell back from Tuesday's gains and was
79.1 points weaker overall at 7,119.6.
</P>
<P>
The big four banks in Australia all lost ground: ANZ bank fell
10.4 cents to 11.59 Australian dollars, National Australia Bank
lost 27 cents to 28.26 Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of
Australia dropped 49.9 cents to 26.15 Australian dollars and
Westpac bank slipped 13 cents to 11.42 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index eased 22.8 points to 987.1 as the spot price of
gold bullion in Sydney was steady at 284.50 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary national turnover was 460.06 million stocks
changing hands for 810.89 million U.S. dollars. Falling stocks
outnumbered rising stocks 795 to 435 while 504 stocks remained
steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
