<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Strike Paralyzes Israeli Public Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 24 (Xinhua) - Some 400,000 employees in
Israel's public sector Wednesday joined a nationwide strike
launched by about 80,000 public workers nine days ago,
effectively disrupting essential services in the country.
</P>
<P>
All government ministries, government hospitals, post offices
and some state-run companies were closed. National television and
radio stations were disrupted, and passenger traffic was entangled
in the Ben-Gurion International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The strike was expected after the Histadrut, or labor
federation, and the Treasury failed to find a compromise in their
talks Tuesday night over a dispute over a wage hike.
</P>
<P>
The Histadrut is demanding a salary hike of 14 percent for 1998
and 1999 to offset the wage erosion by the inflation, which stood
at 8.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
But the Finance Ministry insisted that it would not go higher
than a 3.85 percent increase, which it said is enough to maintain
the real value of wages.
</P>
<P>
The strike is expected to continue into Friday. The Histadrut
will decide Saturday whether the strike will continue into the
Pesach holiday, which falls on next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Senior Treasury officials charged the Histadrut intentionally
used the sanctions before the May elections in order to squeeze
concessions from the government.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Histadrut Chairman Amir Peretz said, "if it
takes elections for the workers to get their due raises, then so
be it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
