<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Embassy Gives Press Conference in Beijing (more added) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia will try utmost to
protect its country, said Yugoslav ambassador to China Slobodan
Unkovic at a press conference exclusively for Chinese press here
today.
</P>
<P>
"If Yugoslavia was invaded, our country will fight back in
accordance with the rights authorized by the Yugoslav Constitution,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
The Serb Federal Assembly has passed a decision that the
Republic "does not accept the presence of foreign military troops
in Kosovo and Metohija," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
He said polls indicated that the Yugoslav people supported such
decision and all political parties also approved the stance,
adding that President Slobodan Milosevic, therefore, will be
responsible for taking corresponding actions in accordance with
the decision."
</P>
<P>
He said Yugoslavia had always expected that the Kosovo issue
could be settled in a flexible approach. However, he stressed, "we
will never abandon our principled stand."
</P>
<P>
Without the authorization of the UN. Security Council, NATO's
any military strikes against Yugoslavia run counter to the UN.
Charter and to the international laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on all peace-loving nations worldwide to help stop
such aggressive actions in the interest of not only Yugoslavia but
also the world peace.
</P>
<P>
NATO secretary-general Javier Solana Tuesday authorized NATO
military forces to launch air strikes against Yugoslavia and
Yugoslavia had declared state of emergency.  
</P>
