<HEADLINE> No Decision on Postponing Declaring Statehood: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians have not decided
whether to postpone the declaration of an independent state,
Palestinian Minister of Planning and International Cooperation
Nabil Shaath said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egypt's Voice of Arab radio over telephone
from Washington, Shaath said that a postponement decision in this
regard must be "preceded by full consultations" among the
Palestinian institutions.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has repeatedly hinted
declaration of an independent Palestinian state on May 4 when the
five-year interim self-rule period enshrined in the 1993 Oslo
Accord expires whether a final settlement is reached in the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel is opposed to the possible move, threatening to take
tough actions against the step, including annexation of the parts
of the West Bank under its control.
</P>
<P>
Shaath was accompanying Arafat in a visit to the United States,
during which Arafat has consulted with U.S. President Bill Clinton
on the possible declaration to win Washington's support for the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Shaath termed the talks held late Tuesday between Arafat and
Clinton as "positive."
</P>
<P>
Arafat will "thoroughly consider the different U.S. ideas" and
submit them to the Palestinian institutions for discussion in an
effort to make a final decision on the declaration of the future
Palestinian state, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Several countries have advised that the Palestinians may
declare their independent state on a later day. Reports have said
the Palestinians will hold a meeting among various groups early
April to seek a decision on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
