<HEADLINE> Japan Extends Grant Assistance to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
decided to extend a grant of some 8.32 million U.S. dollars in aid
to Nepal as the third portion of debt relief measures in its 1998
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Notes in this regard were signed here Wednesday by the Japanese
Ambassador to Nepal and Nepali Finance Secretary Ram Binod
Bhattarai on behalf of their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government provided some 15.9 million dollars to
Nepal in the first two portions of debt relief measures in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been extending the debt relief grant since the last
two decades to help the Nepalese government in procuring such
commodities as petroleum products, fertilizer, medicines, and
construction and transportation equipment.
</P>
<P>
The grant assistance was provided annually in two portions
until Japan's 1997 fiscal year, but it is now being provided in
three portions.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the biggest bilateral donor to Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
