<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Age Disease Strikes 13 Year-old Vietnamese Girl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Nguyen Thi Ngoc, a 13-year-old
Vietnamese girl, looks 70, because she has been struck by a rare
old-age disease, the Vietnam News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The girl is only one-meter tall and weighs just 10 kg. Her skin
is thickened and her finger and toe-nails are almost gone.
</P>
<P>
An Binh hospital in Ho Chi Minh city said Ngoc is suffering
from the Hutchinson-Gilford Progeria Syndrome, a rare disease that
turns children old.
</P>
<P>
International medical experts say there are only 100 cases of
the disease reported world-wide. The cause of the disease is
unknown and no remedy is available.
</P>
<P>
According to the Vietnam News, Ngoc was normal at birth. But
within six months, strange symptoms appeared. Her hair fell out
and she stopped growing when she was one meter tall.
</P>
<P>
Ngoc was brought by her parents to the hospital for the first
time in April 1998 because her nose was bleeding and she had
vomited blood.
</P>
<P>
X-ray revealed that Ngoc has osteoporosis, a condition of
softening bones.
</P>
<P>
She also suffers from diseases commonly found in elderly
people, such as hypertension, heart problems, high levels of
cholesterol in the blood and arteries which decreases the blood
supply to the brain and results in frequent headaches.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts estimate the life span of patients with
Hutchinson-Gilford Progeria Syndrome at 13 to 27 years. Patients
usually die from heart attacks or endocrinological diseases.
</P>
<P>
An Binh hospital said medical science is unfamiliar with this
rare disease and can only offer the girl treatment to maintain her
health, for example, physiotherapy to treat her ankylosis.
</P>
<P>
Ngoc must return to the hospital two or three times a month for
examinations, therapy and medicines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
