<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Zealand Economy Projected to Pick Up Next Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's economy should
pick up during the next two fiscal years, said the Institute of
Economic Research of New Zealand in its latest predictions.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate will be 2.8 percent for the fiscal year from
April 1999 to March 2000 and the momentum in growth will pick up
the following year to reach 4 percent, before easing gradually
over the rest of the study period to 2003.
</P>
<P>
Export growth will be the initial catalyst, although it will
vary widely across export sectors, and will be led by tourism in
the early stages, it said.
</P>
<P>
"However, the recovery will be vulnerable" over the year from
April 1999 to March 2000, it added.
</P>
<P>
Worsening international markets, a strengthening NZ dollar or
another drought could easily undermine growth, the Institute said.
</P>
<P>
The year started with a "hiss and a roar" followed by a host of
 positive indicators for the economy, including improved business
confidence and retail sales, firmer house prices, historically low
 interest rates, and improved trade balance and visitor numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
