<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Higher on Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
higher Wednesday as signs that prices for raw materials were
bottoming out proved positive for the commodity-driven Australian
currency.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed in Sydney at 63.85 U.S. cents after
skipping ahead to 64.08 U.S. cents during the session, its highest
level since late February. It closed Tuesday night at 63.72 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
Gold prices were actually down slightly Tuesday night, but
participants believe the tide may have turned for the precious
metal, at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
Other metals gained ground and added to support for the
Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Copper sustained strong gains Tuesday night, rising 60 U.S.
dollars to 1,421.50 U.S. dollars a tonne and nickel rose 37.50
U.S. dollars to 5,195 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nickel, Lead and zinc also moved higher.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to cut production by oil cartel OPEC sparked the
positive sentiment on commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar often traces movements in commodity
prices because around two-thirds of the country's exports are raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at the close of trading Wednesday, the Australian
dollar was at 75.02 Japanese yen from 75.54 yen and 0.5853 euro
from 0.5846 euro.
</P>
<P>
The euro was buying 1.0905 U.S. dollars from 1.0901 U.S.
dollars and 128.21 Japanese yen from 129.26 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
