<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian Ruling Party Heavyweight Forms New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new party will be led by Namibia's former high commissioner
to Britain, Ben Ulenga, who was a leading member of the ruling
South West African People's Organization (Swapo).
</P>
<P>
Ulenga told a gathering of more than 1,000 supporters and
onlookers that the party would take part in this year's general
elections. The Party's motto would be "A New Beginning," he said.
</P>
<P>
He resigned as high commissioner to London last August in
protest against the lack of open debate in the Swapo as well as
constitutional amendments which will allow President Sam Nujoma to
rule for a third term.
</P>
<P>
According to Namibia's original constitution, the term of
office shall be five years and one may not hold the office of
presidency for more than two terms.
</P>
<P>
Ulenga is the first significant figure within Swapo to openly
break with the party since independence in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He told the gathering that a political vehicle had been forged
to "take people out of disillusionment and give them hope and
direction."
</P>
<P>
The Namibian society was "sick with symptoms of a deadly
disease," he said.
</P>
<P>
These symptoms included the country's military presence in the
Democratic Republic of Congo, the exodus of Namibians from the
Caprivi Strip and a "constitution re-tailored like a dress to fit
an individual."
</P>
<P>
A number of leading government figures are believed to have
expressed sympathy for Ulenga's stand and the idea of forming a
new party.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that none were expected to come forward to
join the party in the immediate future, according to the South
African newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Ulenga was suspended from Swapo's Central Committee last year
for his dissentient views.
</P>
<P>
In 1977 Ulenga was captured for his role in the fight for
independence and was sentenced to 15 years imprisonment on Robben
Island.
</P>
<P>
Following his release in 1985, he was appointed as the general
secretary of the Mine Workers Union of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
After Namibia's independence, Ulenga served as a member of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
He was deputy minister of environment before receiving a
diplomatic posting to London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
