<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Operating System Faces Fierce Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sources with the Beijing Software Engineering and Research
Center under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) note that the
new Chinese log-in system will offer an efficient way for Chinese
TV owners to realize their dream of surfing virtual space.
</P>
<P>
The user-friendly system will not only help TV users process
information and surf the Internet, but will also be widely used in
mini and hand-held computers, as well as the next generation of
personal digital assistance information processing devices.
</P>
<P>
Major domestic enterprises currently manufacturing and
retailing household appliances, as well as a number of computer
companies, have expressed great interest in the Chinese system or
have otherwise inked cooperation contracts with the center.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates unveiled the Venus Operating
System in Shenzhen during his sixth visit to China earlier this
month. Prices for the system range between 1,000-2,000 yuan (120-
360 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Computer experts note that the cost of Microsoft's system will
quite likely be beyond the reach of Chinese consumers, especially
when considering the additional cost for Windows CE. They said
that domestic consumers need low cost products and added that
Chinese software developers are fully capable of competing with
their foreign counterparts in the development of operating systems,
</P>
<P>
China is currently the world's largest market for household
appliances, with 90 percent of households owning 317 million TV
sets and 40 million video compact disk (VCD) players. The
nationwide telephone coverage has reached 25 percent, with the
figure in some cities hitting 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, approximately 95 percent of Chinese families have not
as yet purchased computers. Therefore, the new trend will focus on
the development of products which integrate information technology
with household appliances.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computerization Plans Announced for Processing Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) has announced plans to allow
processing enterprises to apply for trade licenses through its
computer network beginning May 1, this year.
</P>
<P>
Provincial foreign trade and economic cooperation committees
and specified local trade administrations have also been
authorized to approve processing trade.
</P>
<P>
Regional trade administrations at all levels will be required
to transfer data related to approvals or cancellations of trade
licenses to higher authorities on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
China's processing trade sector has witnessed continuing rapid
growth in recent years and accounted for 53.4 percent of the total
export-import volume for commodities during 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, some enterprises have engaged in smuggling or foreign
exchange infractions under the guise of processing trade
activities. Sixty-three percent of 401 smuggling cases reported in
1997 involved processing trade, with the rate approaching 80
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Liu Guosheng, director of MOFTEC's Department of Foreign Trade
Administration, said online approval for processing trade licenses
not only will improve the efficiency of the government, but will
also follow the sector's development and help stop administrative
loopholes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
