<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese to Combat New Health Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese medical experts and
officials warn that any failure to control joint tuberculosis (TB)
and AIDS infections will threaten the health and well-being of the
nation's citizens.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) used today's activities
marking "World Anti-Tuberculosis Day" to call on people around the
world to battle tuberculosis which infects 10 million and kills
some three million people each year.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS weakens the immune system and AIDS patients stand
a 30-50 percent greater chance of contracting tuberculosis. HIV
carriers contracting TB are much more likely to infect healthy
individuals.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Minister of Health, Yin Dakuei, noted that close
to a third of AIDS patients also suffer from TB.
</P>
<P>
An estimated six million Chinese suffer from pulmonary TB, with
two million individuals suffering from highly infectious forms of
the disease. TB hits at least 1.13 million Chinese residents
annually.
</P>
<P>
WHO recommends the use of "directly observed treatment, short
course" (DOTS) which calls for administering daily drug doses to
TB patients over a six-month period.
</P>
<P>
However, approximately half of China's population is not
covered by the DOTS program, with the problem especially acute in
remote poverty-stricken areas, where local people are caught in a
vicious circle of disease and poverty, warns Professor Zhang
Lixing, vice-president of China's Anti-Tuberculosis Association.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Health Yin said that his ministry is expected
to sponsor a national epidemiology survey on TB next year in order
to strengthen the control effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
