<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman to Give Death Penalty to Drug Traffickers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Drug traffickers are to face
death penalty in Oman from now on under a new law enforced through
a royal decree by Sultan Qaboos, the UAE's Khaleej Times daily
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, published in the latest edition of the
Government Gazette, people found engaging in illegal import of
certain specified narcotics and psychotropic drugs would be liable
for capital punishment, the report said.
</P>
<P>
They would be sentenced to death or life imprisonment and
fined up to 25,000 riyals (about 65,000 dollars), the law said.
</P>
<P>
The decree added those found illegally sponsoring activities
that involve the import, exort or production of narcotics and
psychotropic drugs, either directly or indirectly, would meet
with the same punishment.
</P>
<P>
The same punishment, the decree said, would be given to those
who involve a minor in committing such crimes and those who belong
to or cooperate with any international narcotics smuggling groups
or syndicates.
</P>
<P>
The new law will also apply to those found misusing their
powers in either committing or facilitating such crimes.
</P>
<P>
Plants forbidden to be cultivated or imported include Indian
cannabis, charas, ganja, Indian hemp, kif and marijuana, the
decree said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
