<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harvard Economist Optimistic About Asia's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Harvard economist Jeffrey Sachs
said here Wednesday that the long-term perspective for Asia is
positive despite the financial turmoil that has dragged many
economies of the region into a recession.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of Credit Suisse First Boston's
second Asian investment conference, Professor Sachs said the whole
episode of the last two years in Asia was "a bad accident of
bubble bursting leading to financial panic."
</P>
<P>
"But there are no signs of fundamental collapse," said Sachs,
explaining that the panic ended when short-term debt stopped
flowing out of the beleaguered Asian economies in the summer of
1998.
</P>
<P>
He told the 600 participants: "All the reasons that we're
optimistic about Asia for the long term, I believe, are to be true.
The underlying strength of the region is real."
</P>
<P>
In his speech entitled "Major Challenges in East Asia's
Economic Recovery," the Harvard professor called Asia "an
incredibly resilient, dynamic region" with two-thirds of the
world's population and a great ability to adopt technology.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the "dramatic, rare and extraordinary but unnecessary
" withdrawal of short-term international capital from Asia in the
latter half of 1997 for triggering financial panic worldwide.
</P>
<P>
A tough critic of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Sachs
said the IMF rang alarm bell around the globe, creating a dramatic
sense of panic.
</P>
<P>
"IMF is the worst panic involved," said the economist, who on
many occasions rapped the IMF for making rescue packages
conditional on such issues as hiking interest rates and tightening
fiscal policy -- measures he said didn't help in abnormal
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
IMF Asia-Pacific representative Hubert Neiss, also a keynote
speaker at the conference, responded that strategies supported by
the IMF in Asian crisis countries have shown results --
stabilization achieved, recovery under way, and exchange rates
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
But the two shared some common ground on how Asia can move on
along its way of recovery. Sachs pointed out that lack of
liquidity is what Asia is facing now. "We need exchange rate
flexibility and regional cooperation on liquidity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, Neiss said that one of the major elements of the IMF
strategy is to adopt expansionary macroeconomic policies to
support domestic demand. Both of them emphasized that the
restructuring of financial market, banks and corporate are
essential to the pace of recovery.
</P>
<P>
Sachs also stressed that the key to Asia's recovery is its
investment in human resources and its commitment to science and
technology. Both are vital to ensure the underlying long-term
export competitiveness of Asian economies, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
