<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Allied Planes, Ships Ready for Attacks on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and allied warships and
bombers stand ready Wednesday to deliver a "swift and severe" blow
to Yugoslavia, starting with a U.S.-led barrage of sea- and air-
launched cruise missiles that would target Yugoslav air defense
systems and open the way to a larger-scale bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
The decision on when to start the attacks lay with U.S. Army
General Wesley Clark, NATO's top commander. NATO Secretary General
Javier Solana gave Clark the formal go-ahead Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"No alternative is open but to take military action," Solana
said solemnly at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium. He
announced his move just hours after last-ditch talks in Belgrade
between President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. special envoy
Richard Holbrooke ended in failure.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton prepared the nation for an imminent
attack on Serb targets, saying that although American troops would
be at risk, the air campaign is necessary for Europe's long-term
stability. Congress lined up behind him, dropping a move to cut
the financial rug from under U.S. military action.
</P>
<P>
"I want to level with you," Clinton said in a speech Tuesday, "
This is like any other military action. There are risks in it."
</P>
<P>
An opening volley of cruise missiles would be fired from four U.
S. Navy ships and two submarines in the Adriatic, along with one
British sub, plus Air Force B-52 bombers flying from a base in
England. Also likely to be among the first in action are U.S. Air
Force F-117 stealth fighter-bombers based in Italy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Tuesday
that the Yugoslav Army was dispersing its air defense equipment in
anticipation of NATO airstrikes. Yugoslav officials, citing an "
imminent threat of war," declared a state of emergency, mobilized
troops and put the army on a high state of alert.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, appearing Tuesday
night on CNN's "Larry King Live" program, said, "The purpose of
this is to deter Slobodan Milosevic from continuing on his rampage
and going in and torching, having his soldiers and his special
police torch the villages. It is designed to deter that and also
to damage his capability to do that."
</P>
<P>
NATO has a force of 350 to 400 aircraft earmarked for
airstrikes in Yugoslavia. Just under 200 are American.
</P>
<P>
As NATO strikes appeared all but inevitable, Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov registered his opposition by canceling a
Washington visit even as he flew to the U.S. on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to patch up differences with Moscow, Albright
spoke by telephone for more than half an hour with her Russian
counterpart, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, according to Albright's
spokesman, James P. Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Albright told Ivanov she hoped the United States and Russia
could find a way "to deal with the situation and continue to work
in other ways," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Albright also conferred twice by telephone with Solana, the
NATO chief, and talked separately with the foreign ministers of
France, Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate had been scheduled to take a major procedural
vote on legislation by Republican leaders designed to keep Clinton
from using U.S. military power in the Balkans crisis without
support from Congress first.
</P>
<P>
But after Clinton met with congressional leaders at the White
House, Senate leaders shifted gears and expressed support for
airstrikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
