<HEADLINE> Spain Regrets Over NATO Decision to Strike Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Spanish government deplores
NATO's "inevitable" move to use force in its bid to check the
deterioration of tensions in the Balkans, the Spanish Foreign
Ministry said in a communique released early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The communique affirmed that, regardless of what happens, the
Spanish government "will continue to support diplomatic efforts to
put the presently serious situation back under control."
</P>
<P>
The Spanish government aims to continue to work for the signing
of an accord that can ensure the peaceful coexistence of all
ethnic groups in Yugoslavia, the communique added.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on Tuesday authorized NATO
forces to take military actions against Yugoslavia. He told
reporters at the Brussels-based NATO headquarters that he made the
authorization because the last-ditch effort by U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke had failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
