<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Says OPEC Decision Will Stabilize Oil Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar
Zanganeh stated on Tuesday that the recent agreement reached at
the 107th ministerial meeting of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) would stabilize the oil market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) in
Vienna after the OPEC meeting, Zanganeh expressed satisfaction
with the outcome of meeting, in which OPEC and non-OPEC
members agreed to cut their oil outputs by 2,100,000 barrels
per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
OPEC showed once again that it is powerful enough to
overcome market crisis, he said, expressing hope that all the
members would fully honor their commitments.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister underlined the importance of cooperation
of non-OPEC members, and said four non-OPEC oil producers
Mexico, Oman, Norway and Russia have agreed to reduce their
daily oil production by 400,000 barrels, which constitutes 20
percent of the total cut in oil production.
</P>
<P>
"This marks the first time that non-OPEC oil producers
cooperate with OPEC at such level," he said.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC members on Tuesday agreed to reduce their output
ceiling to 22.976 million bpd effective from April by cutting
1.72 million bpd after five major oil producers reached
agreement earlier this month to cut down output in order to
raise prices.
</P>
<P>
The initiative ended a year-long oil price slump and some
oil experts believe that oil price would reach 20 dollars per
barrel if the agreement would be observed by the OPEC members
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the cuts by oil producing countries, Iranian oil
officials said that the recent agreement heralds the end of
the "fourth oil shock," which started in 1997 and intensified
in 1998 due to increase in OPEC output, mild winter and
financial crisis in Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
