<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Parliament Enacts Tax Cut Bills for Fiscal 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Diet (parliament) on
Wednesday enacted a set of six bills aimed at implementing tax
cuts worth 9.4 trillion yen (about 79.9 billion U.S. dollars) in
fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
The tax cuts include cuts to income and corporate taxes as well
as increased deductions for housing loans, which were approved at
the plenary session of the opposition-controlled House of
Councilors, or the upper house of the Diet.
</P>
<P>
The bills, expected to stimulate slumping personal consumption,
are part of key measures by the Japanese government to boost the
stagnant economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the bills, income tax cuts will be implemented
retrospective to January.
</P>
<P>
The effective corporate tax rate will be down to 40.87 percent
from 46.36 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Japan's taxpayers who buy homes within the next
two years will be able to deduct a maximum of about 5.88 million
yen (about 49,000 dollars) from income tax over 15 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
