<HEADLINE> France to Join NATO Military Actions Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- France will take part in North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) military operations related to
the Kosovo crisis, the foreign ministry announced in a communique
released here early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The communique said, "President Jacques Chirac and the
government have decided that French armed forces would take part
in NATO military operations that have become inevitable" after
Belgrade refused to meet the international community's demands to
end all offensives in Kosovo and sign the Rambouillet accords.
</P>
<P>
"By persisting in this attitude during the last-ditch efforts
made with him, President (Slobodan) Milosevic bears the entire
responsibility for the consequences resulting from this refusal,
of which he was fully warned," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The statement went on to say that all political means had been
used to convince the Yugoslav authorities to choose a negotiated
solution and peace, but such means were now exhausted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in Berlin, Chirac, who is there to attend a European
Union summit, signed an "instruction" to French armed forces chief
of staff Jean-Pierre Kelche ordering him to take his forces into
action in line with NATO decisions on Kosovo, presidential
spokeswoman Catherine Colonna said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
