<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Plunging in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued plunging in
Tokyo Wednesday on selling after recent gains, with the key Nikkei
index closing below 16,000 for the first time in three trading
days.
</P>
<P>
After closing below 14,000 on March 2, the Nikkei index surged
almost 2,500 points by the end of last Friday's trading, with
investors now "adjusting their positions following the rally," a
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange nose-dived 503.63 points, or 3.
14 percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 15,515.47.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 30.12 points, or 2.38 percent, to 1,233.
59.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section dropped to 685.37 million shares
from 827.35 million shares Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Akai Electric was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Arbitrage-linked selling, stirred by a fall in index futures
prices, also dampened stock prices, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Share prices declined in all business sectors except the
service industry, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers surpassed
gainers by 863 to 318, with 147 issues unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
