<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT March 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Secretary-General of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) Javier Solana on Tuesday authorized the NATO
forces to take military actions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters here at the Brussels-based NATO headquarters
that he made the authorization because the last-ditch effort by U.
S. envoy Richard Holbrooke failed. Before leaving for Belgrade
Monday to persuade Yugoslav leaders to accept a NATO demand, the
envoy said that he and leaders of Western allies were not
optimistic about his mission on truce in Kosovo. (NATO-Talks
Failure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- Oil ministers of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) agreed here on Tuesday to cut oil
output by 1.7 million barrels a day to boost sagging prices,
announced current OPEC president Yousef Yousfi.
</P>
<P>
Yousfi, also Energy and Mines Minister of Algeria, said he
believes the new cuts, which will take effect on April 1 and
remain effective for a year, will stimulate the oil prices to rise
sharply. He said all the member countries are willing to make
contributions to the efforts. (OPEC-Oil Output Cut)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- The leaders of the 15-nation European Union (EU)
gathered here on Wednesday in a bid to reach a consensus on the
bloc's financial reform and EU executive body's succession.
</P>
<P>
The most important and complicated issue at the two-day summit
is the Agenda 2000 reform package, a program of budgetary changes
aimed at checking costly farm and regional spending to prepare the
union to absorb new members from agriculture-intensive eastern and
central Europe. (EU-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- A senior Russian diplomat on Tuesday night
said that his government is opposing the use of force against
Yugoslavia over the issue of Kosovo, saying such an action,
without the authorization of the U.N. Security Council, violates
the principle of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
Sergey Lavrov, Russian permanent representative to the United
Nations, told Xinhua at a reception in the Russian Mission that
NATO can not be justified by launching military strikes on
Yugoslavia. There are two instances of use of force under
international law, one instance is for the self-defense and
another instance is the authorization of the U.N. Security Council,
he said. (UN-Russia-Kosovo) 
</P>
