<HEADLINE> Manila Expects Rebels to Release Hostages Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Wednesday that National Democratic Front (NDF) rebels may release
five police and military officers next week, when government
forces are to suspend military operations against them.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in an interview that
the government is hopeful that the NDF will respond positively to
the suspension of the military offensive, which will take effect
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The NDF abducted Brig. Gen. Victor Obillo, Capt. Eduardo
Montealto, Sgt. Alipio Lozada and Chief Police Insp. Roberto
Bernal in the past month and another military officer last year.
</P>
<P>
When the government suspends military operations against the
rebel group next week, Zamora said, the NDF is expected to start
releasing the hostages.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada ordered the Defense Department Monday
to suspend military operations against the rebels as a
confidence-building measure aimed at facilitating the safe
recovery of the five abducted officers.
</P>
<P>
The NDF has promised to release the hostages between March 22
and April 19.
</P>
<P>
The government's move was in response to the efforts of an
independent third-party humanitarian group led by Archbishop
Fernando Capalla, which negotiated for the release of the
officers.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has indefinitely suspended formal peace talks with the
NDF until the rebels release the five officers unharmed and
without any conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
