<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's B-Shares Regaining Vitality: Analysts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Slumping B-shares on China's two
stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen have rebounded by 25
percent after hitting all-time lows early this month.
</P>
<P>
The B-share index closed at 26.80 points on the Shanghai Stock
Exchange on March 23, surging 25.3 percent over the low of 21.24
on March 10, and the Shenzhen B-share index has grown 25.1 percent
since its historic low.
</P>
<P>
B-shares are designed and listed on domestic stock exchanges
for overseas investors only.
</P>
<P>
The bearish B-share markets began in May 1997 with the onset of
the Asian financial crisis. Foreign capital from Hong Kong, Taiwan
and Japan, which accounts for more than 60 percent of all funds in
B-shares, began to withdraw, dragging B-share indexes sharply
downward, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
Xu Lan, of the Nanfang Securities Research Institute, was
quoted by today's China Securities Daily as saying that the B-
shares rebound is not surprising.
</P>
<P>
Xu attributed the better performance to the bullish stock
markets in New York and Hong Kong as well as the rally of H-shares
and red chips, both representing Chinese company interests in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average reached the 10,000 point
milestone on March 16, and the Heng Seng Index in Hong Kong has
climbed over 11,000 points, bringing about overseas-investor
confidence, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the promising performance of B-share
companies and the forthcoming favorable policies governing the B-
share markets from China's securities regulatory authorities have
brought new hope to the declining B-share markets, according to
Liu Zhongxue of the Ping'an Securities Research and Consultation
Company.
</P>
<P>
Analysts also pointed out several difficulties facing the
rejuvenation of B-shares, saying that recovery can not be expected
quickly. The implementation of favorable policies needs time, and
detailed measures are yet to come.
</P>
<P>
In addition, poor liquidity and irregularities in the
disclosure of information concerning stock issuance will be major
hindrances to a resurgent B-share market, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
The securities regulatory authorities have already realized
these problems and solutions of them are now under discussion,
sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
