<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Supply Stable in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- An adequate stock inventory
coupled with increased distribution activities enabled the
Philippines to keep the supply and price of rice stable during the
first quarter of 1999, the National Food Authority (NFA) said in a
report published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The NFA said its rice stock stood at 1.1 million tons, or half
of the country's total grains stock, by the end of February.
</P>
<P>
Commercial rice stocks accounted for 16 percent of the total
supply while household rice stocks made up the remaining 35
percent, the NFA said.
</P>
<P>
"With a sufficient beginning stock inventory of rice this year,
the NFA has effectively contributed in assuring the supply and
price stability of the basic staple, particularly for the
January-February period, " it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said the high market visibility of NFA rice has
helped keep the price of rice affordable to ordinary consumers.
</P>
<P>
With the NFA selling its regular-milled rice stocks at 14 peso
(37 U.S. cents) per kilo, retail prices of the staple have
remained as of last month at a per-kilo rate average of 17-18.78
pesos (about 45 U.S. cents), it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
