<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Mayor Puts Letter Box on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Students in this coastal city in
east China's Shandong Province will warm up this winter as the
local government has vowed to replace all outdated heating
facilities at the city's 65 middle schools with automatic heating
installations.
</P>
<P>
However, most of them may not know of this decision, one of 12
key projects announced recently by the government to be undertaken
this year to further improve the people's working and living
conditions. The project was conceived after a complaint letter
directly addressed to mayor@gov.qd.sd.cn, Mayor Wang Jiarui's e-
mail box, was sent by an ordinary resident, Ze Xuwei.
</P>
<P>
Ze was the first to send an on-line letter to the mayor after
the website was launched on January 18. He said he felt a bit
surprised when he learned of the mayor's timely response to his
complaint.
</P>
<P>
"We had taken it for granted that the city's development is the
affair of policy makers, but this time it really gave me a sense
of participation in public affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Like Ze, more than 200 people, including four living abroad,
have posted letters to the mayor through the Internet, and all
have received replies.
</P>
<P>
"It's important to keep our promise to handle every letter
earnestly, or we'll lose the trust of the residents," the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
Wang, 50, who holds a doctorate in economics, is one of the
first few mayors in China to put his letter box on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the letter box will act as a bridge linking the
government and residents," said the mayor in an on-line letter in
English to all residents on the day his site was launched, adding
that he is looking for more convenient and effective ways to get
to know the local people and enhance decision-making.
</P>
<P>
Most of the messages posted to Wang's letter box deal with
criticism of the government and civil servants, proposals for
improving the work of the government, and complaints about social
problems.
</P>
<P>
Cyber-surfers are usually well-educated, Wang noted, so their
opinions may be more insightful.
</P>
<P>
The mayor has managed to find time every day to go through
these letters and usually gives immediate instructions on how to
respond to them.
</P>
<P>
A special section has been set up in the general office of the
city government to coordinate and supervise the handling of these
letters.
</P>
<P>
The mayor gives great attention to criticism and suggestion
letters focusing on weaknesses in areas such as property
development, the environment, finance, and urban communications.
</P>
<P>
"Such contact has helped make our decision-making more
scientific and democratic," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Information Industry of China,
governments at all levels have been moving toward an increased
presence on the Internet this year in order to enhance government
efficiency. The Beijing Municipal Government has just opened a
similar e-mail letter box on the Internet where Beijingers can
post letters to their mayor on various issues. The Guangzhou and
Shenzhen city governments in south China's Guangdong Province have
also launched trial websites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
