<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Trust Firm To Be Restructured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou International Trust
and Investment Corporation (Gitic) is expected to carry out a
restructuring plan to help pull out of its present financial
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The initial restructuring plan was announced here over the
weekend at the first creditors meeting on March 18-19 which was
called by this struggling investment arm of Guangzhou, capital of
Guangdong Province in southern China.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the restructuring will provide a way to resolve
Gitic's problems at present, and place it back on a sound
development track in the long run," said Wu Ziyou, deputy director
of the Guangzhou Development Planning Commission which represents
the city government in handling Gitic's affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman for Price-Waterhouse, the renowned
international accounting firm which has just been invited to
become Gitic's financial adviser, the restructuring aims to create
a financially sound group, and will touch upon Gitic's present
structure, business scope, financial and investment arrangements,
and internal managerial system.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1984, Gitic is the main investment arm of the
city of Guangzhou, and engages in domestic investment, securities
and credit. The bulk of its capital assets are in the Chinese
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Gitic's financial difficulties began to surface late last year
when many of its overseas creditors demanded debt repayment after
the panic triggered by the bankruptcy of the Guangdong
International Trust and Investment Corp., one of the country's
largest trust firms.
</P>
<P>
Poor internal management, rushed investment decisions, and
excessive investment in real estate are believed to be the main
factors responsible for Gitic's current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Unwilling to see Gitic go bankrupt, the Guangzhou city
government has been making efforts to bail it out. Between March
to August last year, the city government helped raise 3.3 billion
yuan (about 400 million U.S. dollars) for Gitic's use in repaying
part of its foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Despite the restructuring plan, Gitic remains in the shadow of
a possible bankruptcy due to pressure from its subsidiary firm,
Guangzhou Finance Company LTD (GFC) operating in Hong Kong, which
is besieged by a liquidation demand filed in the local high court
by 11 overseas financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
GFC's liquidation would severely undermine Gitic's
restructuring plan, said Wu Ziyou. "It is very likely that in that
case Gitic would have no way out but to declare bankruptcy."
</P>
<P>
Wu said he hopes these overseas financial institutions will
calm down and voluntarily withdraw the liquidation demand from the
high court.
</P>
<P>
"That will give the people in Guangzhou time to carry out the
rescue plan which will bring about more benefits to creditors than
a liquidation," said Wu.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that Gitic has invited Baker&AMP;Mckenzie to be GFC's
legal consultant.
</P>
<P>
"Both the city government and business circles have placed high
hopes on Gitic's restructuring," said Wu, who called again for
understanding and cooperation on the part of foreign creditors,
urging them not to demand debt repayment or withdraw their
deposits before the restructuring plan is completed and announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
