<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Joint Venture to Open in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Japanese joint foreign
trade company is expected to begin operations on April 20 in the
Shenzhen Special Economic Zone in Guangdong Province, according to
the International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
The new firm has registered capital of 100 million yuan and is
jointly funded by the China National Cereals, Oils and Foodstuffs
Import and Export Corporation, which holds a 51-percent share, and
the Nichimen Corporation of Japan with a 49-percent share.
</P>
<P>
The former, China's leading foodstuffs and edible oil importer
and exporter, has been included in Fortune magazine's list of the
top 500 companies for four consecutive years, while the latter has
total assets of 19.9 billion U.S. dollars and is involved in 58
joint ventures in China.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC)
has granted approval for the establishment of five Sino-foreign
joint-venture foreign trade companies in Shenzhen and Shanghai's
Pudong New Area.  
