<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solana's Order to Bomb Yugoslavia Draw Mixed Reactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana's order to bomb Yugoslavia has sparked mixed reactions to
the Kosovo crisis which has threatened peace and security in the
Balkans, a traditional power keg in Europe, for over a year.
</P>
<P>
At NATO's headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, Solana told
reporters Tuesday night that he had directed Gen. Wesley Clark,
supreme allied commander in Europe, to initiate air operations in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief did not say when the bombardment will begin, but
it was expected soon.
</P>
<P>
British Defense Secretary George Robertson hinted Tuesday that
NATO would launch air strikes against Yugoslavia on Wednesday
unless Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepts a U.S.-backed
plan which had been signed by the Kosovo ethnic Albanians at the
Paris peace talks last week.
</P>
<P>
"If NATO begins air strikes against Yugoslavia on Wednesday, it
will be with a heavy heart," he told the BBC television.
</P>
<P>
However, the latest NATO sabre-sattling threat failed to force
Belgrade into submission, which refused to accept the deployment
of NATO peacekeepers on its territory as envisaged in the U.S.-
backed plan.
</P>
<P>
The Western powers had hoped that the plan could end the
conflict in Kosovo soon. Kosovo is an Albanian-dominated province
in Yugoslavia's Serbian Republic, where the secessionist Albanians
have been fighting for independence since early last year.
</P>
<P>
In Belgrade, Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir Bulatovic on Tuesday
night declared a nationwide state of emergency, the first time
Yugoslavia has declared since World War II.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian parliament voted unanimously on Tuesday to approve
a resolution, rejecting the presence of a NATO-led force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We do not accept any foreign military troops on our territory
under any excuse, at any price, even at a price of bombing,"
Gorica Gajevic, secretary general of Socialist Party (SPS), told
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Solana's order to strike Yugoslavia received strong support in
Yugoslavia's neighbor, Bulgaria, whose President Petar Stoyanov
said Wednesday morning that Bulgaria will do its best to provide "
humanitarian support" for the NATO action.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian parliament will hold an emergency meeting
Wednesday morning to make a decision on whether to provide an air
corridor for NATO, he said.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, the U.S. Senate gave bipartisan support Tuesday
night to President Bill Clinton's decision to launch NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, even as many Republicans expressed
misgivings about the action.
</P>
<P>
However, NATO's possible military intervention in Kosovo was
strongly opposed by a number of countries including Russia and
China, and could deepen the year-long conflict which Western
powers have hoped to end soon.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov canceled his visit to
Washington Tuesday under the instructions of Russian President
Boris Yeltsin, after being informed of the imminence of NATO
military action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov warned that if
NATO carries out the threatened air campaign, Russia would be
forced to reconsider its relations with the Western military
alliance and take measures to protect its state interests and
prevent the spread of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov also hinted that Russia could provide military aid to
Yugoslavia in case of NATO air raids. He said NATO military
intervention would seriously damage the U.N. resolution imposing
an arms embargo on Yugoslavia, adding that "any country should
have means of self-protection when being invaded."
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev echoed Ivanov's warning.
Upon his return from India, Sergeyev said NATO air strikes would
lead to "serious consequences" and the conflict could turn into "
another Vietnam War."
</P>
<P>
In the United Nations, China Tuesday voiced its objection to
the use of force against Yugoslavia on the issue of Kosovo, saying
the issue should be solved politically through dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Permanent Representative to the U.N. Qin Huasun told
reporters that "any military action against the FRY (Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia) without the authorization of the U.N.
Security Council will be a sever violation of the U.N. Charter and
established principles of international law."
</P>
<P>
"Such action will not be accepted by the international
community," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Permanent Representative to the U.N. Sergey Lavrov said
he would ask for an urgent Security Council meeting if NATO uses
force against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Treasure Sino-U.S. Ties: Chinese Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's
upcoming visit to the United States will strengthen Sino-U.S.
relations, the Chinese Consul General in New York, Qiu Shengyun,
said here Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu will take the opportunity to exchange views on Sino-
U.S. relations and international and regional issues of common
concern and will have wide contacts with people from all walks of
life in the U.S., Qiu said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a gathering with a group of U.S.
journalists who are members of the New York-based U.S. Overseas
Press Club (OPC).
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu will visit the U.S. next month at the invitation of
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
It is the first visit by a Chinese premier to the U.S. in 15
years and a follow-up to the exchange of visits by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Clinton in 1997 and 1998,
which helped bring bilateral ties to a new stage.
</P>
<P>
Qiu cited bilateral cooperation in the economic and trade area
as the most tangible results of the development of the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade rose to 54.9 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 from 2.
4 billion dollars in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The United States is now China's second largest trading partner,
while China is the fourth largest trade partner of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports to China support more than 200,000 high-wage high-
tech jobs and many other job opportunities in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is also the second largest investor in China, where 25,
000 U.S. ventures are set up with a contractual value of over 43
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, some people in the U.S. feel unhappy with the
sound development of Sino-U.S. relations by slandering China for "
stealing" U.S. technology.
</P>
<P>
Describing it as groundless, Qiu said restrictions on high-tech
exports to China will only reduce U.S. enterprises' footing in
China's high-tech market, harming U.S. interests in the long-run.
</P>
<P>
About 30 U.S. journalists attended the gathering.
</P>
<P>
The 60-year OPC has some 600 members, currently or previously
assigned to overseas press posts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
