<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Export Restaurants to World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Export Promotion
Department (EPD) will aggressively promote Thai restaurants to the
international market, with an aim to generate more revenue.
</P>
<P>
Export experts disclosed at a seminar here Wednesday that Thai
export officials have set a four-year target to increase the
numbers of overseas Thai restaurants from 5,000 to 8,000.
</P>
<P>
Starting this year, the department will help potential Thai
food restaurateurs to build a network with foreign investors who
are interested in entering the Thai restaurant business, with the
department acting as a match maker between local operators and
potential foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
Thai overseas restaurants currently generate about 300 billion
baht (8.1 billion U.S. dollars) in revenue for Thailand. The value
is expected to increase by 60 percent if the number of Thai
restaurants meets the four-year target, according to Rachane
Pojjanasunthorn, EPD's deputy director general.
</P>
<P>
"More than 50 percent of the country's revenue is generated
from service industries but most of our human resources are in the
agricultural segment. Therefore, we believe that we can transfer
our people to the service industry since Thais are capable in this
type of business," Rachane said.
</P>
<P>
The department will also conduct an "outgoing mission" by
taking a group of selected Thai restaurateurs to meet potential
partners overseas. At least two or three trips will be organized
annually, with the pilot trip in May to Chicago, Texas, New York
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
As part of the upcoming mission, the department will regularly
organize seminars with international experts in franchise business
to educate Thai operators.
</P>
<P>
It will also help local operators find suitable locations and
conduct feasibility studies.
</P>
<P>
Rachane said, "Most mature markets like the U.S. and U.K.
already have many restaurants. Moreover, developed countries have
strict and complicated regulations for foreign investors.
Therefore, it would be more convenient to enter the markets of
developing countries."
</P>
<P>
According to the department, there are presently 2,000 Thai
restaurants in the United States and Canada, 700 in Europe, 500 in
Australia and 300 in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 70,000 of Thailand's 150,000 restaurants closed
down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
