<HEADLINE> Poland Not Given Final Decision on Joining NATO Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, March 24 (Xinhua)-- Poland has not decided whether or
not it will participate in the NATO military operation against
Yugoslavia, a spokesman from the Polish Defense Ministry announced
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reaffirmed Poland's stand in support of NATO both
in politics and in actions, and right after NATO Secretary-General
Javior Solana ordered air strikes against Yugoslavia on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
If NATO decides to use ground troops in Kosovo, Poland can send
its soldiers there, the spokesman said, while predicting only a
slight possibility of that situation ever developing. Poland,
which just became a new NATO member on March 12, had previously
vowed to send a landing battalion to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The first phase is using the air forces to secure air
superiority," he said. "Only after successful air strikes are
launched can you consider sending land forces in."
</P>
<P>
The 18th land attack battalion is prepared for all possible
fighting and is able to move at any time, said a battalion
official. 
</P>
