<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Garment Exports Drop 15-20 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The garment exports of Bangladesh
declined by 15 to 20 percent in January this year compared with
those of the corresponding month in 1998, said Anisur Rahman
Sinha, president of the Bangladesh Garment Manufactures and
Exporters Association.
</P>
<P>
Some 800 garments industries in the country had to be closed
down, due to natural disasters, political instability, existing
defective systems in customs and property management, additional
charges by banks and insurance and massive devaluation of
currencies in South Asian countries, he said at a meeting with
U.S. Ambassador to Bangladesh John C. Holzman Tuesday, The
Financial Express daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Figures of garment exports in January were not immediately
available. There are over 3,000 garments and knitwear factories in
Bangladesh, employing around 1 million people and contributing to
about 70 percent of the country's total export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Sinha urged the U.S. government to increase export quota for
Bangladeshi garments. "It is very difficult for Bangladeshi
garment sector to compete in the international markets without the
quota facilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also sought support from the Bangladeshi government to help
increase competitiveness of the country's garment sector in the
international market.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Bangladesh would be allowed to export more
than 35 million dozen pieces of apparel products to the United
States and Canada this year under various quota categories,
marking a 10-percent increase over the previous year's figure.
</P>
<P>
The country's garment industry earned approximately 3.8 billion
dollars in the 1997-98 fiscal year ending on June 30, 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil Rebels Target Capital Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil rebels are now
targeting the country's capital Colombo to shift attention away
from their jungle hideout in the north of the country, security
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They said that the rebels, whose strength in the north and east
has been sagging due to several setbacks on the battlefields, are
mobilizing suicide bombers to target individuals and institutions
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Police have already captured six woman suicide cadres who had
been sent to Colombo together with others for these missions, said
a Defense Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The public have been cautioned to be on the lookout for
suspicious characters and for objects, parcels and boxes left
unattended in public places.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Colombo was hit by a spate of terrorist
bomb attacks. Police suspect that Tamil rebels had sent bomb
squads to disrupt civilian life in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Security sources estimate that there are only about 1,500 rebel
cadres left and most of them are in the jungles in the north and
east of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry Tuesday announced that government troops
captured 14 villages and the town of Madhu in Northern province
from Tamil rebels in a four-day operation that ended Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, government troops conducted a similar operation
and captured 24 villages from Tamil rebels.
</P>
<P>
Tamil rebels have been waging a war against the Sri Lankan
government for an independent homeland in the north and east of
the country since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
