<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Prime Minister to Visit Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Prime Minister Phan Van
Khai will pay an official visit to Japan to boost cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Khai will visit Japan from March 28 to 30 at the invitation of
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, according to a communique
issued by the Vietnamese Foreign Ministry Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day visit, Khai will discuss with his Japanese
counterpart how to effectively use Japan's assistance and
cooperation and to design a framework for bilateral cooperation
toward the 21st century, Vietnam News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming visit by the Vietnamese prime minister is the
third visit to Japan by Vietnamese leaders with the first by
Vietnam's then prime minister Vo Van Kiet in 1993 and the second
by then general secretary of the Vietnamese Communist Party
Central Committee Do Muoi in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the second biggest trading partner of Vietnam after
Singapore. Their two-way trade turnover reached 3.23 billion U.S.
dollars in 1998 with Vietnam's exports to Japan worth 1.85 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan ranks the third among foreign investors in Vietnam With
270 projects capitalized at 3.64 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan is also the biggest official development assistance
provider to Vietnam with a total pledged sum of over 4 billion
dollars in the 1992-1997 period, including 491 million dollars
non-refundable aid. In the 1998 fiscal year, Japan committed 853
million dollars assistance to Vietnam. 
</P>
