<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paraguay's Vice President Assassinated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Paraguay's Vice President
Luis Maria Argana was shot and killed Tuesday morning in the
center of Asuncion, the capital of Paraguay, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The attack occurred at 8:50 a.m. local time. Three men dressed
in military uniforms got out of a vehicle and attacked Argana's
car with grenades and high calibre weapons, including rifles. The
car was transporting the vice president to his office.
</P>
<P>
Argana was hit by four bullets, one of which penetrated his
heart and caused immediate death, according to a preliminary
medical report. The driver and bodyguards were also killed in the
attack.
</P>
<P>
President Raul Cubas has ordered the borders closed during the
search for the killers. He has also summoned an urgent meeting of
the cabinet, including police and military chiefs, to examine the
political situation in Paraguay after Argana's death.
The assassination of the vice president "must be clarified," and
those who are responsible will be brought to justice, Cubas said
in a message to the nation while responding to accusations that he
was responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of Argana have accused Cubas of the attack due to
the political disputes between the two over the release of the ex-
military chief, Lino Cesar Oviedo, who was sentenced to 10 years
in prison last March for an attempted coup against former
President Juan Wasmosy in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Oviedo controversy has split Paraguay's ruling Colorado
Party, causing a rift between factions led by Argana and Cubas.
</P>
<P>
The attack added to political turmoil in Paraguay. In a
political fight, the congress voted 71-37 last Thursday to begin
impeachment proceedings against Cubas, who was accused of abusing
power because of a decree last year that freed his ally and mentor,
former army chief Lono Oviedo.
</P>
<P>
After the assassination of Argana, the interior minister
resigned and was replaced by Carlos Cubas, the president's brother.
</P>
<P>
The governments throughout Latin America condemned the attack
and expressed their condolences for the death of Argana.
</P>
<P>
Both banks and exchange markets suspended their activities in
Paraguay due to the incident. A worker from the vice president's
home was detained, according to a TV broadcasting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
