<HEADLINE> Chronology of Major Events Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Following is a chronology of
major events over the troubled Yugoslav province of Kosovo since
early this year.
</P>
<P>
January 29 -- The six-nation Contact Group meeting in London
summons the warring Serbs and ethnic Albanians to attend peace
talks in Rambouillet, near Paris, on February 6, in order to end
an 11-month violence in Kosovo. The U.N. Security Council voices
support for the decision to seek negotiated political settlement
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
February 6 -- The peace talks are opened by host French
President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
February 14 -- The Contact Group extends talks until February
20.
</P>
<P>
February 18 -- NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana threatens
to launch air strikes against Serbian targets if the talks fail.
</P>
<P>
February 20 -- The Contact Group extends the talks until
February 23.
</P>
<P>
February 21 -- Yugoslav army chief General Dragoljub Djdanic
vows to defend Kosovo "at all costs."
</P>
<P>
February 23 -- Major powers say a partial peace agreement is
reached and the two sides will meet again in France on March 15 to
implement the accord.
</P>
<P>
March 15 -- Peace talks resume in Paris. No deadline is given.
</P>
<P>
March 18 -- Kosovo Albanians sign the draft peace agreement on
autonomy in Paris unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
March 19 -- The Contact Group adjourns peace talks, warning
they will not reopen unless Belgrade accepts the autonomy accord.
The breakdown of the peace talks plunges Kosovo into a darker
perspective of bloodshed and war, and increases the risk of NATO
military intervention. Western countries begin to evacuate
diplomatic staffs and their dependents in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
March 20 -- Some 1,400 cease-fire verifiers from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe withdraw from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
March 22 -- U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke arrives in Belgrade on
a last-ditch bid to persuade Milosevic to accept the accord.
</P>
<P>
March 23 -- Holbrooke makes no breakthrough after meeting twice
with Milosevic. Solana orders air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Agrees to Cut Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Oil ministers of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) agreed here on Tuesday to
cut oil output by 1.7 million barrels a day to boost sagging
prices, announced current OPEC president Yousef Yousfi.
</P>
<P>
Yousfi, also Energy and Mines Minister of Algeria, said he
believes the new cuts will stimulate the oil prices to rise
sharply.
</P>
<P>
He said all the member countries are willing to make
contributions to the efforts.
</P>
<P>
The new cuts will take effect on April 1 and remain effective
for a year. The new output quota will be 22.976 million barrels a
day.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum and Mineral Resources Minister of Saudi Arabia Ali
Ibrahim Naimi said the agreement is "very important," and will be
observed. He expected the average oil price to rise to 18-20
dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the biggest oil producer in the world, and it
is the first time it agreed to reduce its output to less than
eight million barrels a day since the early 1990's.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Norway, Oman, Mexico and Russia, all non-
OPEC members, said their countries will also take 400,000 barrels
a day off the market to help boost prices.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC members are Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait,
Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and
Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
