<HEADLINE> Multilateral Agencies Provide Credits to Yemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) announced on Tuesday that it has approved loans and
credits totaling 64 million U.S. dollars to support Yemen's second
annual program under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (
ESAF) and the Extended Fund Facility (EFF).
</P>
<P>
Of the 64 million dollars, about 49 million dollars are
available under the ESAF, and 15 million dollars are provided
under the EFF.
</P>
<P>
The latest disbursements are from a three-year loan and credit
package totaling 506 million dollars that was approved for Yemen
in October 1997. Of the total, 145 million dollars have been
disbursed.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting eligible
members that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payments and improve their growth
prospects, while the EFF an IMF financing facility that supports
medium-term programs that seek to overcome balance of payments
difficulties stemming from macroeconomic imbalances and structural
problems.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the World Bank approved a credit of 50 million
dollars for the Public Sector Management Adjustment Project in
Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said Yemen's economic growth slowed to under 3 percent
in 1998 from 5.6 percent recorded in the previous year and the
external accounts shifted back into deficit as government oil
exports receipts were halved due to the sharp drop in world oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the inflation rate picked up to about 11 percent on
average in 1998, above the target rate of 8.5 percent, spurred
also by the impact of heavy late summer floods on agricultural
prices.
</P>
<P>
Despite the difficult environment, the authorities moved on a
range of structural reforms, including in customs administration,
privatization civil service reform and approval of a modern
banking law, the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF expected Yemen's economic growth rate will rise to 5.3
percent in 1999 while inflation slow to 9.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
