<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Support NATO on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sofia, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian President Peter Stoyanov
said early Wednesday morning that his country has no choice but to
support NATO's decision over the current Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The president urged the government, parliament, and all
political forces in Bulgaria to form a common policy of Euro-
Atlantic solidarity, the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov made the statement after NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana on Tuesday authorized military strikes against Yugoslavia
as the latter refused to accept a Kosovo deal drafted by the six-
nation Contact Group.
</P>
<P>
He said Bulgaria has not been asked by NATO to provide air
corridors for its possible air strikes against Yugoslavia. Thus,
the army is not on an alert.
</P>
<P>
"I believe there is no need for this now," said the president.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the instability in neighboring Yugoslavia had been
affecting Bulgaria's development, both politically and
economically, for too long, the president said "no one wants more
than the Bulgarians a peaceful and fast settlement to the conflict.
"
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out the possibility to postpone his planned
visit to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov urged Bulgarians to stay calm because "there is no
reason to be panic and take unusual action."
</P>
<P>
"What struck me the most in the address of the NATO Secretary
General was the remark that the doors will stay open for a
peaceful outcome," said the president. 
