<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Official, Experts on Millennium Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government said
the country has ample time to deal with the Y2K computer bug,
while information technology experts warned Indonesia is running
out of time, local newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is enough time. The important thing is we make it a
priority based on public need," Research and Technology Minister
Zuhal said here Tuesday regarding the country's ability to prepare
for the bug that is expected to create chaos in computer systems
as the world enters its third millennium.
</P>
<P>
However, Riyanto Gozali, system integration general manager of
PT. Astra Graphia-Information Technology, said April 30 is the
deadline for efforts to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
"We have time until April 30 to deal with it. After that, we
won't be able to make it," he noted.
</P>
<P>
As most computers use only two digits to store the date, they
are expected to mistake the year 2000 for 1900, creating a system
jam, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We're now talking about replacement, not upgrading. Computers
using Intel Pentium 386, for instance, cannot be upgraded. They
must be replaced," the expert said.
</P>
<P>
"So, we're talking about purchase, delivery and set-up. That's
why April 30 is the deadline," Riyanto said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the critical date of September 9, 1999, when
problems related to the millennium bug are feared to make their
debut, Zuhal said: "We should be careful on that date. Matters
from the public domain are crucial, like Garuda Indonesia Airways.
That should be prioritized."
</P>
<P>
"Other priorities include banking, insurance,
telecommunication, aviation and electricity," he added.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the problem, the minister said, the government has
established a special team.
</P>
<P>
Another information technology expert said efforts to overcome
the Y2K problems must prioritize public safety, money and
credibility sectors.
</P>
<P>
Public safety includes airline and traffic system, finance
including banking, while credibility must include customer service
activities such as billing cycles and systems for utilities as
well as payroll systems, he elaborated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
