<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Cases Down in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Health Minister Pradip
Nepal said Wednesday that the number of tuberculosis patients in
Nepal has decreased to about 80,000 from some 100,000 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the occasion of the 117th World Tuberculosis
Day which falls on Wednesday, the minister said the number of
patients dying from tuberculosis has also fallen to about 11,000
from some 16,000.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the official RSS news agency as saying that 34
percent of tuberculosis patients in Nepal have benefited from the
directly observed treatment short course (DOTS).
</P>
<P>
He said the number of new cases in the country has gone down as
well from about 50,000 to the present 44,000.
</P>
<P>
As the success rate of the DOTS has been more than 85 percent,
the International Union Against Tuberculosis and Lung Diseases has
considered Nepal as a model case in Southeast Asia, the minister
added.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala said in his message that
the DOTS has been introduced to 35 districts in the country and it
will be introduced to the remaining 40 districts in the Ninth
Five-Year Plan period (1997-2002).
</P>
<P>
RSS said that the World Tuberculosis Day will be celebrated in
Nepal under the theme of "Use DOTS and Stop Tuberculosis."
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, the National Tuberculosis Center of Nepal is
implementing an urban tuberculosis control program in the
Kathmandu Valley, the first of its kind in Asia, RSS said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Opposes Military Action Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior Russian diplomat
on Tuesday night said that his government is opposing the use of
force against Yugoslavia over the issue of Kosovo, saying such an
action, without the authorization of the U.N. Security Council,
violates the principle of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
Sergey Lavrov, Russian permanent representative to the United
Nations, told Xinhua at a reception in the Russian Mission that
NATO can not be justified by launching military strikes on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
There are two instances of use of force under international law,
one instance is for the self-defense and another instance is the
authorization of the U.N. Security Council, he said.
</P>
<P>
For the first instance, "this is not the case," for the second
instance, "this is also not the case," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is no international law providing for the use of force
against any sovereign and independent country simply for the
humanitarian concerns, one of the major factors used by the U.S.-
led NATO to justify its threat of the use of force against
Yugoslavia, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no international law about the right of the
intervention because of humanitarian considerations," he said, "
Some countries promote this, but this has not yet become law."
</P>
<P>
Russia remains firmly against the military strikes on
Yugoslavia, saying that such an action, without the authorization
of the U.N. Security Council, violates the principle of the U.N.
Charter
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council, under the Charter, has primary
responsibility for the maintenance of peace and security in the
world at large.
</P>
<P>
"Many members of the Security Council and most members of the
United Nations are very much concerned about the possibility of
bypassing the United Nations mechanisms and the United Nations
Charter provisions in the matter of using force," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's dangerous about the very fundamentals of the existing
international system," he said, "Any attempt to use force by
bypassing these mechanisms, I believe, will be detrimental to the
future of the U.N., not for the sake of the U.N., but for the sake
of the collective security system which is embodied in the United
Nations Charter."
</P>
<P>
The Russian envoy made the remarks shortly after NATO Secretary-
General Javier Solana authorized NATO forces to take military
actions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"If NATO begins to use force against Yugoslavia, I will call a
Security Council meeting to see what other Council members are
thinking about," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council convened several urgent sessions in the
past to discuss the situation in Kosovo at the request of the
Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO threatened Belgrade with force in a bid to
force it into accepting a Western-offered peace plan, but
Yugoslavia said it is ready to enter into negotiations on Kosovo
and reject any imposed ideas on the solution of the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
