<HEADLINE> Japan's Destroyers Fire Warning Shots at Suspicious Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Japanese destroyers fired warning
shots early Wednesday at two suspicious ships discovered in
Japanese waters off Niigata and Ishikawa prefectures on Tuesday,
said the Japanese Defense Agency.
</P>
<P>
But the two ships ignored the shots and orders from the
Japanese destroyers to stop and continued to head north, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese warships took the action after the government
invoked for the first time the Self-Defense Forces (SDF) law's
Article 82, which allows necessary maritime patrol measures by the
country's military.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Maritime Safety Agency (MSA) patrol vessels initially
chased the two suspicious-looking boats on the high seas and later
fired 1,200 warning shots at the ships Tuesday night but failed to
stop them.
</P>
<P>
According to the agency, the two ships were disguised as
fishing vessels and had Japanese names. Their true nation of
origin has yet to be identified.
</P>
<P>
The first of the two vessels was spotted about 45 kilometers
east of Noto Peninsula in Ishikawa Prefecture at about 9:25 a.m.
Tuesday, the MSA said.
</P>
<P>
The second was confirmed at about 1 p.m. after destroyers were
dispatched to intercept the ship, it said.
</P>
<P>
The two roughly 100-ton ships were about 30 meters each in
length. No fishing equipment could be seen on deck.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi on Tuesday set up a task
force to deal with the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
