<HEADLINE> Six Bulgarian Doctors, Nurses Expected to Be Freed Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Six Bulgarian doctors and nurses,
who were detained for an investigation into the reported AIDS
cases in Libya, are expected to be freed soon, according to a
message from Omar Mustafa al-Muntasser, Secretary for Foreign
Affairs of Libya to Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadezhda Mihailova.
</P>
<P>
Procedures on the release of these people have been launched,
said the message.
</P>
<P>
The six people, along with their 13 colleagues, were arrested
on February 10, in a hospital in Benghazi, northeastern Libya,
where they were working on an assistance mission. The 13 people
were released last month.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarians' arrest came after cases of the disease were
registered in that hospital. No legal grounds were given for the
arrest but the Libya authorities said they were wanted for
investigation into the AIDS infection.
</P>
<P>
"The arrest was motivated only by concern over the health of
the Libyan residents," the message said.
</P>
<P>
The message stressed that the Libyan authorities are working
in absolute transparency, justice and impartiality, without any
discriminating preconceptions concerning the nationality of the
arrested.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, Omar Mustafa al-Muntasser voiced his hope that
the two sides will continue to work for the final solution of this
problem and for the promotion of bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Media reports in Sofia have said that these Bulgarians were in
trouble with the Libyan authorities for divulging information of
AIDS cases, whose existence in Libya had been officially denied by
the Libyan government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
