<HEADLINE> Primary Schools for Children of Migrant Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest city,
has established 140 primary schools for children of the three
million migrant laborers now living in the city, according to a
report in today's Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Lubinghua Hope primary school, the first primary school for
these children in Shanghai, now has more than 1,800 students, most
of whom are from neighboring Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
Huang Jiasheng, the school's director, said that he founded the
school in 1993 and it now has 118 faculty members.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly speaking, our classrooms and teaching equipment are
much shabbier than those in regular schools, but we can still
guarantee an education quality," said Wang Jianguo, director of
another such primary school.
</P>
<P>
Many of these schools are now seeking good teachers, and more
than half of the teachers in Lubinghua school have Bachelor's
degrees. The schools also employ some retired experienced teachers.
</P>
<P>
"We want to expand our school system to include middle schools
and try to provide the full nine year's of compulsory education to
the children of migrant laborers," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of people, mainly able-bodied laborers in
poor rural areas, have flooded into big cities to seek greener
pastures since China's reform and open-up drive started two
decades ago. How to provide regular education for their children
has become a pressing problem in many cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
