<HEADLINE> Primakov Returns Home on News of Possible Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov canceled a trip to Washington in mid-flight and returned
home because of the deepening crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Primakov stopped off at Ireland's western Shannon Airport
earlier on Tuesday en route to Washington to meet U.S. officials,
but the U.S. later said he had postponed the trip because of
likely NATO military action against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Vice-President Al Gore received the news in a telephone
call with Primakov after the Russian leader had left Shannon for
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Primakov used his brief visit to Ireland earlier on Tuesday to
reiterate Russia's strong opposition to NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"It (air strikes) defies common sense and could destabilize the
situation in the world. We are categorically against this,
categorically," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, a government spokesman said Primakov postponed his U.
S. visit after Gore told him NATO strikes against Yugoslavia had
become "inevitable."
</P>
<P>
"After a conversation with Al Gore from on board the plane, a
conclusion has been made that the strikes are inevitable. Under
such circumstances, it is impossible to carry out a successful
visit," Andrei Korotokov was quoted saying.
</P>
<P>
"So the visit has been postponed. The decision has been agreed
between Primakov and President (Boris Yeltsin)," he said, adding
that he expected Primakov to return to Moscow at around 7 a.m.(
0400 GMT) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a report from on board Primakov's plane, Russia's Itar-Tass
news agency said the prime minister was informed by a Russian
ambassador during his stopover in Ireland that last minute talks
between Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
Primakov was due to attend a regular Washington meeting of an
inter-government commission on economic and scientific cooperation;
he was to co-chair the meeting with Gore. His trip was also seen
as crucial in the government's efforts to win U.S. backing in
talks with the International Monetary Fund on new credits.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev has warned
NATO that air strikes against Yugoslavia could provoke "a new
Vietnam inside Europe."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
