<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Strongly Opposed to NATO Action Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin is
strongly opposed to NATO military action against Yugoslavia and
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov has postponed his visit to
Washington under Yeltsin's instructions, officials said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Prikhodyko, deputy director of Yeltsin's office, told
reporters that Yeltsin has repeatedly expressed his strong
opposition to any NATO military action against Yugoslavia and he
is now closely following the situation in Kosovo, the Albanian-
dominated province in southern Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Prikhodyko said Yeltsin had written to U.S. President Bill
Clinton Tuesday night on the Kosovo issue. But Prikhodyko did not
give details of Yeltsin's reply.
</P>
<P>
NATO General-Secretary Javier Solana Tuesday ordered airstrikes
against Yugoslavia in Brussels, Belgium a few days after
Yugoslavia's Serbian delegation refused to sign a peace plan at
the Paris peace talks. But he did not say when the bombardment
would begin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's press secretary Dmitri Yakushkin said Primakov, who
was over the Atlantic on his way to Washington for a regular
Russian-U.S. economic meeting, decided to return home Tuesday
after U.S. Vice President Ale Gore confirmed that NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia are unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
In their telephone conversations, Gore told Primakov that NATO
bombardment could be conducted during Primakov's visit to
Washington. Primakov is expected to arrive in Moscow early
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Describing NATO's imminent action as a "naked aggression"
against the country, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
underlined Russia's strong objection to NATO military intervention
in Kosovo where the secessionist Albanians have been fighting
Yugoslav security forces for over a year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on an independent television, Ivanov said Russia is
now monitoring the developments in Kosovo and is ready to react
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if NATO carries out its threat, Russia would be
forced to reconsider its relations with NATO and take measures to
protect its state interests and prevent the spread of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said any concrete measures would be determined by
Yeltsin in accordance with the developments in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said NATO military intervention would seriously damage the U.
N. resolution imposing an arms embargo on Yugoslavia, adding that
"any country should have means of self-defense when being invaded.
"
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said the U.N. resolution was observed by the Yugoslav
side but the Kosovo Albanians have been able to get a large amount
of weapons.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev echoed Ivanov's warning
against NATO.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from a visit to India, Sergeyev said NATO
military action in Kosovo would lead to "serious consequences" and
the conflict could turn into "another possible Vietnam War."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that NATO action was a "unilateral act impairing
the rights of a sovereign country and member of the U.N. Security
Council." 
</P>
</TEXT>
