<HEADLINE> Finland to Close Embassy in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Finland is to close its embassy
in Belgrade and evacuate its diplomatic staff there in face of
possible NATO air strikes against the federal republic over the
current Kosovo crisis, said a report of the Finnish News Agency
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Pertti Torstila, a senior official of the
Foreign Ministry, as saying that the embassy staff were ordered to
get ready for evacuations early morning on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A weak possibility that the current crisis in the troubled
Serbian province of Kosovo might be eased still exists as Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic maintains phone contacts with
international mediators including U.S. Kosovo envoy Richard
Holbrooke, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke failed his final rounds of a last-minute peace
mission as Belgrade refused to accept a Kosovo peace deal.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana authorized NATO
military forces to launch air strikes against the federal republic,
yet he did not say when the strikes will begin. Yugoslavia, in
return, declared "the state under an immediate threat of war" on
Tuesday night. 
</P>
