<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Backs NATO Strikes Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian President and Chief
Commander of the Armed Forces Petar Stoyanov announced here on
Wednesday morning that his country supports NATO airstrikes
against Yugoslavia,
</P>
<P>
Speaking at state television hours after NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana ordered airstrikes against Yugoslavia, the president
said Bulgaria will do its best to provide humanitarian support to
the NATO action, including receiving part of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian parliament will hold an emergency meeting
Wednesday morning to make a decision on whether to provide an air
corridor for NATO, he said.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov said he has also canceled his planned trip to Germany
to attend an international book fair because of this emergency.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov canceled his
scheduled visit to Kazahkstan and Kirghizstan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Bulgaria recalled family members of embassy staff from
Belgrade and warned their citizens not to travel to Yugoslavia.
</P>
