<HEADLINE> URGENT: U.S. Senate Votes to Approve Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate gave
bipartisan support Tuesday night to President Bill Clinton's
decision to launch North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, even as many Republicans expressed
misgivings about the action.
</P>
<P>
On a vote of 58 to 41, the Senate gave its blessings to an air
campaign ordered earlier in the day by the NATO, which appeared to
be imminent.
</P>
<P>
"The case of inaction is unacceptable to the world," said
Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner.
</P>
<P>
The final vote, however, was hardly an overwhelming show of
support. Thirty-eight Republicans and three Democrats opposed the
resolution. 
</P>
