<HEADLINE> Serb Parliament Rejects NATO Force for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian parliament voted
unanimously on Tuesday to approve a resolution, rejecting the
presence of a NATO-led force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Passed by 204 to nil with one abstention, the resolution
strongly condemned NATO's sabre-rattling around the borders of
Yugoslavia, warning if a war was imposed on them, they would
defend themselves against aggressors with all means.
</P>
<P>
"We do not accept any foreign military troops on our territory
under any excuse, at any price, even at a price of bombing,"
Gorica Gajevic, secretary general of Socialist Party (SPS), told
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The document noted that threat of military strikes by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization against Yugoslavia was not only no
good to a peaceful settlement to the Kosovo crisis, but also
fanned the fire of separatism and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanian guerrillas in Kosovo, a province of Serbia,
began fighting for independence a year ago, but last week their
political representatives settled for autonomy guaranteed by NATO
troops for an interim three-year period under a plan drafted by
Big Power mediators.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian delegation to the peace talks in France refused to
sign the plan, calling it secessionist and saying NATO troops
would end Belgrade's sovereignty over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of talks between U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade didn't change
the country's stance of rejecting NATO-led force to enter Kosovo.
NATO is now determined to launch air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
