<HEADLINE> First R&AMP;D Center for Returned Students Set Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China's first research and
development (R&AMP;D) center for returned Chinese students was opened
last Saturday in the coastal city of Yantai, Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The center will help these scholars start their own business
and carry out their research projects, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The center was set up by 32 returned Chinese students to
conduct research, development, imports and promotion of high
technologies in new materials, bio-engineering and computer and
computerization. The Yantai Development Zone sponsored these
ambitious young people with 2 million yuan (U.S.$240,000) to make
their dreams come true.
</P>
<P>
Ai Fanglin, deputy director of the Overseas Study Service
Center under the Ministry of Education, said, "the state welcomes
students to return to the motherland after they finish their
education abroad and will create favorable conditions for them.
</P>
<P>
According to Ai, over 300,000 young Chinese have gone to study
abroad since China opened its door to the world at the end of the
1970s. About one-third of them have returned home and become key
members of their work units.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the number of returnees has grown
steadily at an annual rate of 13 percent, said Ai.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Yantai and Shanghai took the lead by establishing
special industrial parks for returned Chinese scholars. By the end
of 1998, more than 23 cities across the country had followed suit,
becoming hosts to over 1,000 enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
