<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Water-Saving Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China has a pressing need to
develop agriculture which uses water efficiently in a bid to
ensure security of food supplies and alleviate poverty in its vast
arid areas, according to a senior Ministry of Agriculture official.
</P>
<P>
"Half of the country's arable land is afflicted by a water
shortage. Some 43 percent of China's population lives in arid
regions," Vice-Minister Lu Ming was quoted as saying by today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, droughts reduce grain output by 30 million tons a
year, Lu said at a national agricultural conference held over the
weekend in Shaanxi Province, one of the northwest China driest
areas.
</P>
<P>
"Grain production is expected to remain at about 500 million
tons at the end of the century, and reach 800 million tons in the
next 30 years. Arid farm land will play a crucial role in
increasing future output," said Lu.
</P>
<P>
Per capita farm land and forests in the 16 northern provinces
and regions are respectively 1.34 and 1.15 times the country's
average, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Arid land in these areas produces 46 percent of the country's
grain, 61 percent of cotton, 72 percent of soybean, and 46 percent
of edible oil products, said Lu.
</P>
<P>
Poverty always goes hand in hand with aridity and other
difficult natural conditions, Lu said, adding that this has made
it all the more important to develop agriculture in these regions
which uses water efficiently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helsinki Stress Low Cost in 2006 Winter Olympics Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Helsinki, the Finland's capital,
Tuesday underscored its relatively low cost in hosting the 2006
Winter Games which they are bidding for with Norway.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish bid's promoters presented its details of the 2006
Winter Olympics bid Tuesday, on which the International Olympics
Committee will make its decision in June.
</P>
<P>
Martin Saarikangas, chairman of the bid committee, said that
the plan would cost an estimated 600 million U.S. dollars, of
which 480 U.S. dollars would be covered by broadcasting rights.
</P>
<P>
Helsinki will co-host with Norway with the venues split between
three cities including indoor events in Helsinki, cross-country
skiing in Lahti, Finland, and Alpine skiing in Lillehammer, Norway,
the site of the highly regarded 1994 games.
</P>
<P>
"We hardly need to build anything. It's all there,''
Saarikangas said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"Helsinki would have to build an athletes' village and a
skating arena," he added.
</P>
<P>
Also in the running are the Italian city of Turin, Sion,
Switzerland; Klangenfurt, Austria; Poprad-Tatry, Slovakia; and
Zakopane, Poland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
