<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diesel-Powered Automobiles Encouraged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China is encouraging diesel-
powered vehicles in a bid to save fossil-fuel resources and lower
auto-exhaust emissions.
</P>
<P>
Experts say diesel vehicles provide better fuel economy and
discharge lower amounts of hydrocarbon and carbon-monoxide
emissions than gasoline vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Du Fangci, a researcher with the State Administration of
Machinery Industry, said that the "state regulatory authorities
are in the position to promote development of high-performance and
lower-emission diesel vehicles" through setting standards and
enhancing management.
</P>
<P>
"It is a step in the right direction for China's automakers to
develop diesel vehicles," Du was quoted by China Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Quality and Technical Supervision
has recently tightened standards concerning vehicle exhaust
emissions. To come into effect on January 1, 2000, they also cover
diesel-powered vehicles.
</P>
<P>
But currently in cities like Lanzhou, Urumqi and Xiamen, local
regulations prevent diesel-powered light commercial vehicles such
as "Transit," "Iveco" and some trucks from entering these cities,
since they are believed to be a major source of air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The annual output of diesel vehicles in China has been about
400,000 during the past few years, most of which were heavy-duty
trucks and buses, accounting for less than 30 percent of total
vehicle production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
