<HEADLINE> Blair, Clinton Discuss Military Plans on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and U.S. President Bill Clinton on Tuesday discussed military
plans for possible NATO military strikes on Yugoslavia, a British
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Blair and Clinton had discussed specific
details of targets that would be hit by NATO. But he gave no
detail of when the repeatedly warned attack would take place.
</P>
<P>
"They reviewed the situation on the ground in Kosovo and
discussed military plans," a Reuters report from Dublin, the
capital city of Ireland, quoted a spokesman for Blair as saying.
</P>
<P>
Blair, on his way to Germany capital Berlin to attend a
European Union summit, stopped at Dublin to hold talks with Irish
leaders on the peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the two leaders talked for 15 minutes on
telephone after U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke reported to NATO that
he had failed to persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
accept the Kosovo peace plan initiated by the West.
</P>
</TEXT>
