<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Loan Helps Rehabilitate Quake-Hit Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The reconstruction program in
Lijiang, an ancient southwest China town damaged by a strong
earthquake three years, has been completed with the help of an
emergency World Bank loan.
</P>
<P>
Local officials announced recently that more than 400
reconstruction projects have been completed.
</P>
<P>
A strong quake measuring seven degrees on the Richter scale
devastated Lijiang and surrounding areas in Yunnan Province on
February 3, 1996. The quake caused direct economic losses of over
four billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Lijiang is known for its unique cultural heritage, especially
its ancient and unique buildings. The World Bank provided
emergency assistance loans totaling 348.6 million yuan, with the
Chinese government providing an additional 177 million yuan for
the reconstruction effort.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 million yuan had been invested in the reconstruction
program by the end of 1998. The World Bank loans were mainly used
for rehabilitating 2,000 houses, four water plants, six hospitals,
15 middle schools and 35 primary schools, as well as a number of
ancient relics.
</P>
<P>
The project has enabled 30,000 local youngsters to continue
their education.
</P>
<P>
World Bank officials have expressed great satisfaction with
Lijiang's success and local officials have been invited to recount
their experiences during a bank meeting scheduled for Rome in
October.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
