<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT March 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Tuesday stressed
their support for the United Nations Mission in Bosnia and
Herzegovina (UNMIBH) and called upon the leaders of both entities
to honor the Dayton Peace Agreement.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the 15-
member council, Qin Huasun of China, said, "Council members
reaffirmed their support for the UNMIBH in fulfilling its mandate
in police monitoring, restructuring and reform, in assessment of
the judicial system and in strengthening the legal system's
respect for human rights."
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the Security Council discussed the
report of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the UNMIBH.(UN-
Bosnia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- There is almost no chance for a peaceful solution of
the Kosovo crisis, the German government announced Tuesday while
the German Defense Ministry finished preparing for coming air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that the Holbrooke mission is fruitless, and it's
not the fault of Holbrooke's negotiating talent, but because of
the irresponsible and inacceptable line of Milosvic," German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said at an executive session of the
ruling Social Democratic Party (SPD).(Germany-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov abruptly
postponed a planned trip to Washington Tuesday after he was
briefed by U.S. Vice President Al Gore on unsuccessful diplomatic
efforts to resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Russia has steadfastly opposed threatened NATO airstrikes
against Serb targets in the province.
</P>
<P>
"After discussing the worsening situation in Kosovo, Prime
Minister Primakov decided to return to Moscow," Gore said in a
statement. (Russia-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana Tuesday
authorized the use of military force to resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Solana had directed NATO Supreme Commander General Wesley
Clark to begin military intervention in the Kosovo crisis with air
operations against military targets in Yugoslavia, a Reuters
report from Brussels said.
</P>
<P>
The move came after final attempts at a diplomatic solution
broke down.(NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir Bulatovic declared a
"state of immediate threat of war" on Tuesday night with NATO
poised to launch air strikes against the country over the Kosovo
issue.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovic read out the declaration on state television.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Germany closed their embassies in Belgrade late
Tuesday and urged their citizens to leave Yugoslavia immediately
after the 11th-hour talks between Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke failed. (Yugoslavia-
NATO) 
</P>
</TEXT>
