<HEADLINE> Russian Skaters Impressive at Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Title holders Anjelika Krylova
and Oleg Ovsiannikov of Russia took the lead in the ice dance as
they won both the paso doble and the tango romantica compulsory
dances at the world figure skating championships here on Tuesday
</P>
<P>
They were winners of the two compulsory dances on the cards of
all seven judges while the skaters from French and Canadian were
tied in second place.
</P>
<P>
The second-place tie developed after Shae-Lynn Bourne and
Victor Kraatz of Canada beat Marina Anissina and Gwendal Peizerat
in the first dance only to lose to the French couple in the second.
</P>
<P>
On the same day the near-perfect Plushenko, 16, posted a
decisive victory on the cards of all nine judges in the short
program, vaulting to the top of the men's standings.
</P>
<P>
Another Russian Yagudin, 19, messed up the landing of the
second jump in a triple axel-triple toe loop combination and
dropped to second place overall.
</P>
<P>
Three-times world champion Elvis Stojko placed third ahead of
American Michael Weiss and Russian Alexei Urmanov.
</P>
<P>
Guo Zhengxin of China made a mark as he became the first skater
to do a quad jump in the world championship short program since
permission was granted last year to include it in that section of
the event.
</P>
<P>
Guo came in eighth after he managed a quadruple toe loop but
made mistakes on other elements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
