<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Supports Efforts to Resolve Kosovo Crisis Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam supports efforts to resolve
peacefully the crisis in Kosovo, a spokesperson for the Foreign
Ministry said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesperson told foreign pressmen that Vietnam follows
with keen interest the developments in Kosovo, and hopes the
situation there stabilizes soon so that the Yugoslavian people can
restore and develop their country.
</P>
<P>
"Vietnam is against the use of force which will cause losses to
the civilians, create tension, and threaten peace, stability and
security in the region in particular and the world in general,"
the spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesperson reaffirmed Vietnam's consistent position that
each country's independence and sovereignty and each nation's
right to make decision for itself should be fully respected
without interference into each other's internal affairs, and all
conflicts should be settled through peaceful means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Declares State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir
Bulatovic declared "the state under an immediate threat of war" on
Tuesday night with NATO poised to launch air strikes against the
country over the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovic read the declaration on state television. He said the
decision had been taken because of repeated "threats of aggression
" by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"After consultation with the Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and the speaker of the lower house of the Yugoslav
parliament Milomir Minic," the government made the decision in
line with the constitution, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time Yugoslavia has declared a nationwide state
of emergency since World War II.
</P>
<P>
The government ordered the measure after President Milosevic
refused to accept a Kosovo peace deal, which the ethnic Albanians
had signed in Paris, France, last week. The statement came after
the final rounds of a "last-minute peace mission" with U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke failed to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and NATO have confirmed the threat of military strikes
against Yugoslavia. On Tuesday, NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana authorized NATO military forces to launch air strikes
against the federal republic.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief advised reporters in the Brussels-based NATO
headquarters of the final authorization, but he did not say when
the military action will begin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
