<HEADLINE> Keegan Gives Owen Fitness Ultimatum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- England wonderkid Michael Owen has
been given until Thursday to prove his fitness for the Euro 2000
qualifier against Poland by England coach Kevin Keegan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We want him fit but if he's not involved in training at
Wembley on Thursday, I personally would be loath to play him on
Saturday," said Keegan.
</P>
<P>
The new manager's preparations for the match have already been
disrupted by a number of players suffering from niggling injuries
and the withdrawal of David Batty.
</P>
<P>
The Leeds midfielder is suffering from a chest infection and
his absence leaves the England squad in serious need of back-up as
they prepare for a game in which victory is a prerequisite.
</P>
<P>
The absence of Batty, who had been expected to partner Jamie
Redknapp in central midfield, is especially worrying given that
Paul Ince is suspended and Nicky Butt is injured.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, the Leeds player's absence is likely to improve the
chances of Tim Sherwood or Ray Parlour winning a first cap, but
Keegan may well decide to call on his former Newcastle captain
Robert Lee or even West Ham midfielder Frank Lampard for more
reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
Defender Andy Hinchcliffe was also added to Keegan's injury
list after he was ruled out of Saturday's game at Wembley with a
back injury.
</P>
<P>
The absence of the Sheffield Wednesday full-back leaves Graeme
Le Saux and Phil Neville vying for the left-back spot.
</P>
<P>
Robbie Fowler and Darren Anderton were also missing when
England trained at Bisham Abbey on Tuesday although Keegan has yet
to confirm whether they are carrying injuries.
</P>
<P>
The former Newcastle boss has already been sweating on the
fitness of Chris Sutton (groin), David Seaman (shoulder) and Nigel
Martyn (back) and none of the quartet took part in this morning's
session at Bisham Abbey.
</P>
<P>
If Seaman and Martyn fail to improve before Saturday, Keegan
will have to put his faith in Ian Walker - a last minute call-up
to provide the final line of defence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
