<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall Sharply On Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
fell sharply Tuesday in fears by investors about lower company
earnings and higher bond interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed down 218.68 or 2.2 percent at 9,671.83, losing
momentum for closing above 10,000. The index crossed the five
digit milestone several times last week in intraday trading.
</P>
<P>
The blue chip stocks got the second-worst point loss this year
and sank below 9,700 for the first time since March 9.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were even lower than the Dow. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 34.87 or 2.7 percent at
1,262.14 and the technology heavy Nasdaq index was down 73.10 or
3.1 percent at 2,322.84.
</P>
<P>
Fears spread among investors after Merrill Lynch said the
Coca-Cola company would reduce its sales growth because of
economic crises in Latin America and Japan. Investors had got
uneasy about earnings of technology companies such as Dell
Computer and IBM.
</P>
<P>
Investors were also worried about bond interest rates. The
30-year Treasury bond yield was down to 5.56 percent Tuesday, but
still above 5.5 percent, the level which would disturb both the
stock and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 15.04 to 595.45 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 14.04 to 703.32. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 9.83 to 383.37.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 675 up, 2,360 down and 504
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 808.66 million shares from 656.21
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
