<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Declares State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir
Bulatovic declared a "state of immediate threat of war" on Tuesday
night with NATO poised to launch air strikes against the country
over the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovic read out the declaration on state television.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Germany closed their embassies in Belgrade late
Tuesday and urged their citizens to leave Yugoslavia immediately
after the 11th-hour talks between Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke failed.
</P>
<P>
Greece urged any of its nationals in Yugoslavia to leave,
although it said embassy staff would stay on.
</P>
<P>
Greece reportedly prepared 50 buses to evacuate some 2,000
Greeks from Yugoslavia across Bulgaria to Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Foreign Ministry called on Italians to cancel all
journeys to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Air France, British Airways, Swissair and Lufthansa announced
Tuesday to cancel scheduled flights to Belgrade because of the
threat of NATO air strikes, which has been authorized.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov Tuesday canceled a trip
to the United States, turning back after a stopover in Ireland as
NATO forces prepared to attack Serbian targets.
</P>
<P>
ITAR-TASS news agency said the trip was canceled after US Vice
President Albert Gore spoke to the prime minister about "imminent
strikes" against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been opposing use of force against Yugoslavia to
settle the Kosovo issue. 
