<HEADLINE> Solana Orders Air Operations in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana Tuesday authorized the use of military force to resolve the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Solana had directed NATO Supreme Commander General Wesley Clark
to begin military intervention in the Kosovo crisis with air
operations against military targets in Yugoslavia, a Reuters
report from Brussels said.
</P>
<P>
The move came after final attempts at a diplomatic solution
broke down.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Balkans envoy Richard Holbrooke told NATO ambassadors
earlier that he had failed to persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to call off his army in Kosovo and sign a peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
But Solana did not give any timing for the start of air
strikes. He only said he wanted to make it clear that NATO was
"not waging a war" against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
NATO knows the risks of taking action but inaction carries
greater dangers, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is not known when the operations will begin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
