<HEADLINE> Pentagon Outlines 1st Phase of Attack Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO would bring a barrage of
U.S. cruise missiles from Navy ships and submarines and Air Force
bombers aimed at "blinding" Yusoslavia's extensive network of air
defense radars and missiles in its first phase of attacks, U.S.
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will take very seriously the threat posed by this air
defense system and do our best to suppress that, as well as
looking at other targets," Pentagon spokesman Ken. Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
Once the air defenses had been damaged, a variety of manned
aircraft, including U.S. and allied F-16s and American F-15s,
would have a less risky opportunity to target weapon depots and
Serb troop concentrations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. officials declined to discuss a timetable for
beginning the attacks but indicated they were imminent.
</P>
<P>
In a further sign that NATO action was approaching, Bacon said
Yugoslav military officers who had been stationed at a NATO air
operations center in Italy since last year as part of an exchange
agreement were being sent home.
</P>
<P>
One factor being weighed by allied military officials was the
poor weather forecast for Yugoslavia Wednesday, which would not be
a problem for cruise missiles but would hamper efforts to assess
bomb damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
