<HEADLINE> Germany Foresees No Chance of Peace in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 23 (Xinhua) -- There is almost no chance for a
peaceful solution of the Kosovo crisis, the German government
announced Tuesday while the German Defense Ministry finished
preparing for coming air strikes.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that the Holbrooke mission is fruitless, and it's not
the fault of Holbrooke's negotiating talent, but because of the
irresponsible and inacceptable line of Milosvic," German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said at an executive session of the
ruling Social Democratic Party (SPD).
</P>
<P>
U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke returned to headquarters
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in Brussels
Tuesday after Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic rejected his
peaceful bill.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder told SPD leaders that NATO would take strike actions
as planned. "We will do this until Milosevic comes back to the
basis of humanity and international law," he said.
</P>
<P>
The German Defense Ministry said that the German air force
Luftwaffe had been "fully prepared" for NATO air strikes, and up
to 15 Tornado fighters with 500 soldiers would take part in one
turn of attack against Yugoslav targets.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Defense Ministry said it was "absolutely
necessary" for the government to put Tornado fighters in action
from the very beginning of air strikes, because the fighter was
able to evade surface-to-air missiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
