<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Local Government in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday
approved a loan of 100 million U.S. dollars for the local
government finance and development project in the Philippines,
aimed at improving the capacity and strengthening the capability
of the local government units.
</P>
<P>
The project's main objective is to assist participating local
government units in expanding and upgrading their basic
infrastructure, services, and facilities; and in strengthening
their capacities in municipal governance, investment planning,
revenue generation, and project development and implementation,
the bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The project reinforces the bank's long-standing commitment to
strengthen fiscal decentralization and local self-reliance in the
Philippines," said Thomas Zearley, principal operations officer in
the World Bank East Asia and Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the project is consistent with the Philippine
government's objectives of strengthening public policies and
implementation capabilities; improving the country's
infrastructure and facilitating growth, particularly by mobilizing
private investment and participation; and alleviating poverty and
upgrading basic social services.
</P>
<P>
Total costs of the project are 133.7 million dollars. The World
Bank's loan of 100 million dollars is at the bank's standard
interest rate for LIBOR-based U.S. dollars single-currency loans,
with a maturity of 20 years, including a five-year grace period.
The balance of 33.7 million dollars will be provided by the
Philippine government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
