<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Ends Emergency Talks, Heads for NATO HQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- United States special envoy
Richard Holbrooke ended his two-day emergency talks with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic and headed for NATO headquarters in
Brussels on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The American diplomat said before departing that his "tortuous"
talks with the Yugoslav president did not achieve much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Ends Emergency Talks, Heads for NATO HQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Holbrooke, who came here on Monday after a stopover in
Brussels, held a four-hour talk with President Milosevic and
discussed with the presidential security thinktank in Washington
over phone the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
He told the press before leaving Belgrade that he conducted two
days of intense talks with President Milosevic and his associates.
"We emphasized two things: we see an evidence that there would be
a cease-fire of the military operations going on in Kosovo; the
readiness to enter into prompt actions that will lead rapidly to a
NATO-led force in Kosovo in accordance with the Rambouillet
accords."
</P>
<P>
He described the talks as very intense and tortured between the
Contact Group, western countries and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The American envoy, who brokered last October cease-fire
agreement, said that the NATO-led force would neither be pro nor
anti any ethnic group in the Yugoslav province but favor only the
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Though President Milosevic said repeatedly that his side would
not agree to the NATO-led peace implementation force, Holbrooke
said that he could not see any amendments forthcoming even after
consultation with U.S. President Bill Clinton and U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke's team was instructed by Washington to go to Brussels
and meet with the NATO allies before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
The American diplomat said that it would be misleading to
define his talks as having made any positive movement.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the end of his talks with the Yugoslav
president meant a status of war had been established, the American
special envoy said that this was not in his ken to answer.
</P>
<P>
He added that the president in the White House was the one to
answer that question.
</P>
<P>
But Holbrooke stressed that communications are always open,
even in times of conflict and that international mediator
Christopher Hill would return to Skopje in neighboring Macedonia
and Belgrade has his telephone number there.
</P>
<P>
He declined to say whether it would be his last diplomatic
effort but that the question had to be dealt with by others.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo observers here tended to believe that Holbrooke had had
something from his talks this time with President Milosevic but
that the thing may be difficult for NATO to accept before
rendering it possible to make the current face-off soften somehow.
</P>
<P>
Last October it was through Holbrooke's shuttle activities
between Belgrade and Brussels that finally led to the cease-fire
agreement and the deployment in the Yugoslav province of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe-led Kosovo
Verification Mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
