<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Protect Traditional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- African countries should avoid
enacting legislation under the segregative Trade Intellectual
Property Rights Agreement, an expert said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Johnson Epkere, scientific research consultant with the
Organization of Africa Unity (OAU), said the agreement did not
recognize the rights of African communities to traditional and
indigenous knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Epkere said this on the second day of the southern African
regional workshop on the Intellectual Property Rights here in the
Zimbabwean capital.
</P>
<P>
If African countries rushed to implement the agreement, he
said, it would lead to unjustified exploitation of their knowledge
and biological resources by foreign corporations.
</P>
<P>
"African countries should develop suitable legal systems of
protecting their own plant varieties, indigenous knowledge and
technologies and community rights consistent with national
priorities," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was important for African governments to be wary of threats
that were posed by multi-national corporations and unethical
science and technical research teams from western countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Only Egypt, South Africa and Zimbabwe had legal instruments to
comply with the agreement because their existing laws protected a
number of plant varieties, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
