<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Flower Growers Use Int'l Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's 11 rose growers who
export flowers into Europe have been accredited to the
International Flower Label Program, a pilot project which
guarantees cut flowers produced under socially and environmentally
sustainable conditions.
</P>
<P>
Spokesperson of the Zimbabwean Flower Growers Association
Pauline Alexander Tuesday told the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana that
the Zimbabwean farmers were the second to be granted such
recognition after Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The International Flower Label Program sets out criteria for
cut flower production.
</P>
<P>
"This includes the safe use of pesticides, worker protection,
strict registration procedures of spraying programs, re-entry
intervals, protective clothing, staff training courses, blood
analyses and strict environmental protection," Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
Horticultural Promotions Council director Stanley Heri said,
"having established ourselves as a producer of quality flowers, it
was essential to maintain that reputation and improve on it."
</P>
<P>
Another country participating in the Flower Label Program was
Kenya, while growers in Zambia, India and Israel had expressed
interest to join, Alexander said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
