<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Praises PNA for Thwarting Terrorist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Tuesday praised the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
for helping thwart a terrorist attack against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Tel-Aviv after a three-day visit to
Ukraine, Russia and Georgia, Netanyahu called the PNA's help "a
positive step."
</P>
<P>
But he said the PNA was not operating systematically against
terrorism, claiming that other killers of Jews were being freed by
the PNA after they were detained.
</P>
<P>
About three weeks ago, the PNA uncovered a plan of the Islamic
militant group Hamas to launch an attack in central Israel, and
passed the information on to the Israeli security forces.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Radio said that a wide-scale manhunt was
underway for a Hamas member, Mahmoud Abu Hunoud, who was
suspected of planning the attack.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that Abu Hunoud might have received the orders
and cash payments from overseas Hamas leadership to carry out the
attack in the coming days. But his plan was foiled by Israeli and
Palestinian security forces.
</P>
<P>
Abu Hunoud, who has been at large since 1994, was also
suspected of involvement in several suicide bombing attacks in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Early Monday, Israeli security forces raided the house of Abu
Hunoud near the West Bank city of Nabulus and detained his father
and some other relatives.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, which rejects the peace agreements between Israel and
the PNA, has carried out since 1994 several terrorist attacks that
resulted in the deaths of scores of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Last October, the PNA and Israel signed a land-for-peace
agreement in the United States, under which the PNA should take
tougher measures against terrorism in return for the further
withdrawal of Israeli troops from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But Israel suspended the implementation of the agreement in
December, accusing the PNA of not fulfilling its commitments.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security sources said the recent cooperation between
Israeli and Palestinian security forces suggested that the PNA was
making efforts to prevent any terrorist attack against Israel
before the May elections in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that by helping Israel, the PNA wanted to
convince the U.S. and European countries that it had fulfilled its
part of the commitments under the peace pact.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a brother of a top Palestinian
security official was charged by an Israeli military court
Tuesday with recruiting members for Hamas.
</P>
<P>
The defendant, Yasser Rajoub, is a brother of Jibril Rajoub,
head of PNA's Preventive Security Services in the West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
