<HEADLINE> Internet Access Expected to Rise in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Internet penetration is
projected to rise to one third of U.S. households by the end of
1999 and close to two thirds by the end of 2003, from the current
25 percent level, a U.S. research firm reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Consumers are expected to spend 56 billion U.S. dollars on
Internet access services over the next five years and the market
is forecast to grow at an annual rate of 21 percent, said the
Massachusetts-based Yankee Group following its latest study.
</P>
<P>
Falling personal computer prices are enabling more households
to buy the devices to get on-line, said the company, which has
found that 46 percent of U.S. households with PCs cite the
Internet as the main use for their computers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
