<HEADLINE> Arafat Urges Israel to Implement All Peace Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Palestinian
Leader Yasser Arafat on Tuesday urged Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to honest and implement all peace agreements
completely.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Arafat met with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan this morning. It was widely seen here that Arafat, who has
said he might declare a Palestinian state on May 4, 1999, was seeking
consultation from the United Nations on what should happen on and
after May 4.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Arafat said his talks with the U.N.
chief was positive and constructive, and Annan voiced his support
for all the U.N. resolutions on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he was sorry that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu had frozen all negotiations and meetings on the peace
process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Under an interim peace agreement signed in Cairo in May 1994,
Israel and the Palestinians were to have completed talks on the
final status of the Palestinian territories by May this year.
Those negotiations have hardly started.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is under pressure from the U.S. congress and the Clinton
administration to postpone a unilateral declaration of statehood
on May 4.  
</P>
</TEXT>
