<HEADLINE> U.N. Volunteers Coordinator in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Sharon Capeling Alakija, the U.N.
Volunteers' Executive coordinator, arrived here Tuesday to start
her four- day working visit to Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Alakija is coming to have direct contact with the volunteers in
 Mozambique, and kick off the celebration plan for 2001, which has
been labeled as the International Year for Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official will call on leaders of Mozambique and visit
Beira and tour Tete province to inspect the activities of the U.
N. volunteers there, according to a statement issued here Tuesday
by the U.N. Development Program.
</P>
<P>
She will also deliver a speech on the promotion of volunteers'
involvement in social development at a forum to be held in Maputo
Friday, and cut the ribbons for the completion of the Home of U.N.
Volunteers..
</P>
<P>
U.N. volunteers started operations in the country in 1979, with
their activities mainly in health, education and technical
consultation. There are now 60 U.N. volunteers in Mozambique.
</P>
