<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garten Says U.S. Benefits by Getting China into WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Blocking China from the World
Trade Organization would be a serious mistake for it would
undercut U.S. commercial and security interests, Jeffrey E. Garten
said in his article entitled "The Wrong Way to Punish Beijing",
published in the New York Times Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"As the rage over China's alleged theft of American nuclear
secrets continues to seethe in Washington, Congress will be
looking for ways to punish Beijing," said Garten, the former under
secretary of Commerce for International Trade in the first Clinton
Administration. "The obvious move would be to deny China" entry
into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Garten, now dean of the Yale School of Management, pointed out
that U.S. would "benefit if China sticks to a path of economic
reform,and the WTO provides powerful reinforcement for Beijing to
do so". "By becoming a member of the WTO, China would in effect be
signing a treaty committing itself to becoming a market economy,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that joining the WTO would "force China to open
its markets, American industry, agriculture and banking would gain
great advantages".
</P>
<P>
"China's membership in the WTO would support our national
security too", he continued. "Surely we have a better chance of
seeing a peaceful and prosperous China if it is inside the WTO
tent, adhering to the rule of law, rather than outside of it."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
