<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Helps Finance Uganda's Hyacinth Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian government has given
Uganda a grant of 18 billion shillings (18 million U.S. dollars)
to help control water hyacinth in water bodies of the country.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Specioza Kazibwe, who arrived in Cairo Sunday,
will sign the agreement during her current visit to Egypt,
Tuesday's New Vision newspaper quoted a press release from her
office as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The press release said that Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Agriculture and Land Reclamation Youssef Wali was
deeply impressed by Uganda's speed in handling the joint program
to control the water weed.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will also help Uganda with irrigation and water
management besides training Ugandans in biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
Last year a team of Egyptian experts came to help Uganda solve
the water hyacinth problem. Countries drinking water from the Lake
Victoria have resolved to rid the lake of the water hyacinth which
causes environmental problems and a lot of inconvenience for
people's lives.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government has used chemical, physical, biological
and mechanical methods to remove this prolific plant. But water
hyacinth is still found on water surface because it floats and its
removal can cost more than the country can afford. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UPOV Welcomes China's Accession to Plants Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The head of the International Union
for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV) has welcomed
China's accession to the organization.
</P>
<P>
By depositing its instrument of accession to the International
Convention for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants here Tuesday,
China will become the 39th member of UPOV on April 23.
</P>
<P>
Kamil Idris, Secretary General of UPOV and Director General of the
World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO), said that by
protecting the rights of plant breeders, the membership of the
People's Republic of China would contribute to promoting agricultural
development and ensuring food security.
</P>
<P>
UPOV, an intergovernmental organization based in Geneva, cooperates
in administrative matters with WIPO.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the UPOV convention is to acknowledge the
achievements of breeders of new plant varieties by granting them an
exclusive property right on the basis of a set of uniform and clearly
defined principles.
</P>
<P>
To be eligible for protection, varieties have to meet certain
conditions such as being distinct from existing, commonly known
varieties and sufficiently homogeneous and stable.
</P>
<P>
Protection is given to plant breeders both as an incentive to the
development of agriculture, horticulture and forestry, and to
safeguard the interests of plant breeders. Improved varieties are a
necessary and cost-effective ingredient for achieving food security in
a sustainable way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
