<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Names Acting Special Envoy in Western Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General on
Tuesday presented a report to the U.N. Security Council, saying
that he has appointed Robin Kinloch, chairman of the
Identification Commission, as Acting Special Representative in
Western Sahara to facilitate the proposed referendum on the future
of the territory.
</P>
<P>
The appointment, with immediate effect, followed the
resignation of the special representative, Charles F. Dunbar,
</P>
<P>
"On March 31, 1999, my special representative's previously
agreed term of service will come to an end, and I have accepted
his resignation effective that date," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan also proposed the extension of the mandate of
the United Nations Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara
(MINURSO) until April 30. The current mandate is to expire on
March 31.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 255 MINURSO members from 28 countries,
including China, Argentina, Egypt, France, Malaysia, Nigeria,
Russia and the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
