<HEADLINE> Uganda to Interdict Incompetent Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has directed Minister of Public Services Amanya Mushega to
interdict officials who are named in the parliamentary select
committee report as having been responsible for mismanagement of
the livestock project.
</P>
<P>
The president's directive was contained in a statement
presented to Parliament Tuesday by the Minister of Presidency
Ruhakana Rugunda on the report of the select committee on
agriculture, Radio Uganda reported Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The officials to be interdicted include former Permanent
Secretary Opika Opoka and other senior officials in the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Museveni also directed investigations to establish whether a
project consultant used money from the livestock services to build
his private school.
</P>
<P>
The president has noted that the main problem with government
projects is poor conception and design. That is why there are
consequential problems during implementation.
</P>
<P>
Museveni also thanked the select committee for the work it has
done and said that the executive and the legislature have a
complementary role in improving the management of public affairs
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The 100-page report by the select committee holds that Vice
President Specioza Kazibwe, who is also the Minister of
Agriculture, Animal Industry and Fisheries, and two state
ministers in her ministry should take political responsibility for
shoddy work done in the construction of all the 15 valley dams.
</P>
<P>
The mismanagement of the valley dam project is alleged to have
made the government lose 3.4 million U.S. dollars. Many MPs demand
to censure Kazibwe for that.
</P>
<P>
However, Rugunda said that Kazibwe is currently on an official
visit to Egypt and requested Parliament to give her time to
present her side of the story during the ongoing debate. 
</P>
