<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and
Supply Ahmed Gowaili conferred Tuesday with Ugandan Minister of
Trade and Industry Moses Ali on issues of mutual interest in
trade, economic and investment fields.
</P>
<P>
The talks also dwelt on ways of fostering bilateral cooperation
through holding public and specialized trade exhibitions, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to offer needed facilities in this fields,
the news agency said, adding that Uganda would grant Egypt a vast
area to showcase its products.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition of Egyptian products will be organized in Uganda
later this year. An Egyptian trade official has said that Uganda
has agreed to provide the exhibition of location free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The discussion between the two ministers also covered the
possibility of funding each country's foreign trade companies to
boost bilateral trade, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt seeks all means to enhance trade and economic ties with
other members of the Common Market of Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA), which Egypt joined in June 1998, Gowaili was quoted by
the news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Uganda tops the countries with which Egypt is keen on fostering
trade ties due to the geographical and traditional trade relations
binding them, he said.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Egypt and Uganda stood at 7.4 million
Egyptian pounds (2.18 million U.S. dollars)in 1997, with 4.8
million pounds (1.41 million dollars) worth of Egyptian exports.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan official arrived in Cairo on Monday. 
