<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Ends Emergency Talks, Heads for NATO HQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- United States special envoy
Richard Holbrooke ended his two-day talks with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and was heading to NATO headquarters in
Brussels on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The American diplomat admitted before departure that his
"intense and tortured" talks did not achieve any positive
movement.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, who came here on Monday after a stopover at the NATO
headquarters in Brussels, held a four-hour talk with President
Milosevic and then discussed with the U.S. presidential security
thinktank in Washington over phone the rest of the night on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He held talks with the Yugoslav president for another three
hours on Tuesday before making phone calls in the embassy again.
</P>
<P>
He told the press before leaving Belgrade for Brussels that he
conducted two days of intense talks with President Milosevic and
his associates.
</P>
<P>
"We emphasized two things: the evidence that there would be a
cease-fire of the military operations going on in Kosovo; the
readiness to enter into prompt actions that will lead rapidly to a
NATO-led force in Kosovo in accordance with the Rambouillet
accords," he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the talks as very intense and tortured between the
Contact Group, western countries and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The American envoy, who brokered last October cease-fire
agreement, said that the NATO-led force would neither be pro nor
anti any ethnic group in the Yugoslav province but favor only the
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Though President Milosevic said repeatedly that his side would
not agree to the NATO-led peace implementation force, Holbrooke
said that he could not see either any amendments forthcoming even
after consultation with U.S. President Bill Clinton and U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke's team was instructed by Washington to go to Brussels
and meet with the NATO allies before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
The American diplomat said that it would be misleading to
define his talks as having made any positive movement.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the end of his talks with the Yugoslav
president meant a status of war had been established between the
Balkan nation and NATO, the American special envoy said that this
was not in his ken to answer.
</P>
<P>
He added however that the president in the White House was the
one to answer that question.
</P>
<P>
But Holbrooke stressed that communications are always open,
even in times of conflict and that international mediator
Christopher Hill would return to Skopje in neighboring Macedonia
and Belgrade has his telephone number there.
</P>
<P>
He declined to say whether it would be his last diplomatic
effort but that the question had to be dealt with by others.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo observers here tended to believe that Mr. Holbrooke
might have had something from his talks with President Milosevic
but that the thing may be difficult for NATO to accept before
rendering it possible to thaw the current face-off.
</P>
<P>
Last October it was through Holbrooke's shuttle activities
between Belgrade and Brussels that finally led to the cease-fire
agreement and the deployment in the Yugoslav province of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe-led Kosovo
Verification Mission.
</P>
<P>
Monday and Tuesday's was Holbrooke's second trip to Belgrade in
three weeks during the current crisis while he came to Belgrade
three times last October before pinning down the agreement between
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and NATO and the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
