<HEADLINE> UN Approves Further Four Contracts for Iraq's Oil Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Sanctions Committee approved a further four contracts for Iraq's
oil industry in the past week, U.N. Office of the Iraq Programme
said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The office said it received a further seven contracts in the
past week and the four approved, worth of 888,239 U.S. dollars,
are for Iraq's oil industry spare parts and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The office said to date, it has received 564 contracts with a
total value of 295.5 million dollars and 395 contracts worth 237
million have been approved.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council adopted a resolution in
February 1998, which allows Iraq to sell 5.2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of oil every six months to ease the deteriorating
humanitarian situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also permits Iraq to import 300 million dollars
worth of spare parts and equipment to update its oil industry and
promote its capability of producing oil.  
</P>
