<HEADLINE> Turkey, Syria to Improve Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Syria will further
boost their economic and commercial ties, Turkish Deputy Prime
Minister Hikmet Ulugbay said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ulugbay made the remarks after meeting with his Syrian
counterpart Salim Yassin, who arrived here Monday for a two-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in 12 years that Turkish and Syrian
officials sat down to discuss ways of strengthening economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The last economic gathering between Turkey and Syria took
place in 1987. In the following years, bilateral economic ties
weakened as a result of Syrian support for the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Ulugbay said that joint studies are underway in an effort to
tap the great potential in commercial and economic cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are working on drafting an agreement on
prevention of double taxation and a deal on protecting and
encouraging investments, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also decided to promote their cooperation in
tourism.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between Turkey and Syria in 1998 reached 615
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turkey exports synthetic materials, iron and steel, margarine
and automotive products to Syria and its main import from Syria
is crude oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
