<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Support from Congress on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Tuesday met with lawmakers to seek support for U.S. military
action in Kosovo as his special envoy Richard Holbrooke reported
little progress in his talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and prepared to leave Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, after meeting with his foreign policy team, gathered
key members of Congress in the White House residence, to impart
the latest information and "make the case for the policy he is
pursuing" White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters. "It's
our hope and our expectation that we will get bipartisan support."
</P>
<P>
The president stated his opposition to an effort in the Senate
to block fund for the mission to airstrike Yugoslav targets,
Lockhart said. Republican Senator Kay Bailey Hutchison said after
the meeting that lawmakers would alter the funding proposal.
</P>
<P>
"There will be, probably, a different kind of amendment,"
Hutchison said. "It becomes a different issue when action becomes
imminent. While many people may disagree with the president's
policies, I would not want Mr. Milosevic to get the impression
that (U.S. forces) may not get full support."
</P>
<P>
Democratic Senator Bob Kerry said he has serious concerns that
getting involved in Kosovo -- coupled with other U.S. deployments
in Bosnia, South Korea and Iraq -- would stretch military
resources too thin.
</P>
<P>
"There's only a certain number of things we can do. I would
have preferred to say in this instance to the Europeans, 'This is
one you're going to have to do'," Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
Still, Clinton "has made the case to me... so I'll support
him," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton then made a speech after the meeting, saying the United
States and its NATO allies were "united and prepared" to take
military action against Yugoslav targets.
</P>
<P>
He said if Milosevic was not willing to sign a Western-drafted
peach deal on Kosovo, then the United States and its allies are
willing to limit his ability to make war.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore said earlier at an American Legion
session that the United States is "determined to act to diminish
the military power...and help the Kosovar Albanians win the
safety, security and self-government they deserve."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the State Department warned Milosevic not to lash
out beyond Kosovo in the event of a NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
there would be "great consequences" if Milosevic sent troops
beyond Serbia's borders, the State Department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
