<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opposes Use of Force Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- China Tuesday voiced its
objection to the use of force against Yugoslavia on the issue of
Kosovo, a Serbian province, saying that the issue should be solved
politically through dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, the Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, told reporters that "the question of Kosovo is an
internal matter of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY)."
</P>
<P>
"Any military action against the FRY without the authorization
of the U.N. Security Council will be a severe violation of the
U.N. Charter and established principles of international law," he
said. "Such action will not be accepted by the international
community."
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government believes that it should be settled
politically through dialogues, on the basis of respect for the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of the FRY and the guarantee
of the legitimate rights and interests of the ethnic groups in the
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "we urge the relevant parties to adopt a
restrained, patient and flexible attitude and continue to seek a
proper and fair settlement of the issue of Kosovo through
negotiations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador made the statement after the U.S.-led
NATO issued repeated warnings to Belgrade that it would risk
getting bombed if it refused to accept the peace plan drafted by
the Western countries.
</P>
<P>
China maintains that only the U.N. Security Council has the
primary responsibility in the maintenance of peace and security in
the world at large, and any military action against a sovereign
and independent country should be officially authorized by the
15-member council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
