<HEADLINE> Britain Closes Embassy in Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Tuesday it had
closed its embassy in Belgrade and all remaining staff were being
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
"Our embassy has already been closed and all our staff are
leaving Belgrade," a Foreign Office spokesman told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made as the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
is planning action against Serbian military sites in the province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Office confirmed that all the remaining staff,
about five, are being pulled out. It is not clear yet if all of
them have left the country.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair said earlier that Britain
stands ready with NATO to launch air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Both the United States and Germany had said they had also
suspended their embassy operations.
</P>
<P>
The US told its embassy in Belgrade to close and is evacuating
all the embassy staff in case of NATO attacks on Serbian targets,
a US State Department spokesman said in Washington.
</P>
<P>
US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright gave the order for
security reasons after a briefing from U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke, who had just back from a visit to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Holbrook had failed to persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to sign on the peace treaty initiated by the West.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, report from Russia said that Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov had cancelled his scheduled visit to the US
because of the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
