<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's South Aswan Iron and Steel Company signed a
deal with the Hong Kong Shanghai Bank on Tuesday, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the bank will provide a loan of 420 million
U.S. dollars to finance a project of the company.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Industry and Mineral Resources Suleiman
Reda, who attended the signing ceremony, said the signing of the
deal mirrors a stable Egyptian economy and the role played by the
private sector in staging big projects.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's trade deficit of the second quarter of the
1998-1999 fiscal year stood at 2.21 billion Egyptian pounds (650
million U.S. dollars), the Central Bank of Egypt said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the period from October to December, Egypt exported 1.93
billion pounds (568 million dollars) worth of goods while its
imports amounted to 4.14 billion pounds (1.22 billion dollars), a
monthly report issued by the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The report said the first quarter of the fiscal year also
witnessed a trade deficit, which stood at 3.07 billion pounds (903
million dollars), including 1.08 billion pounds (318 million
dollars) in exports and 4.15 billion pounds (1.22 billion dollars)
in imports.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Italy on Tuesday signed a cooperation
protocol in electricity and non-conventional energy fields,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, the two countries will set up a joint
committee for energy, grouping experts on both sides. It will
meet twice a year in Rome and Cairo alternatively.
</P>
<P>
The committee is to be in charge of drawing up plans and
programs aimed at boosting bilateral technical cooperation in the
fields of power generation, transfer and distribution.
</P>
<P>
It will also oversee bilateral cooperation in the area of new
and renewable energy.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's Central Bank said on Monday that its gross
foreign reserves stood at 6.554 billion U.S. dollars, up 259 million
dollars in the first half of March.
</P>
<P>
The increase was mainly brought up by the issue of eurobonds
worth of 540 million dollars during February.
</P>
<P>
Reserves stood at 6.148 billion dollars in 1998, up from 5.931
billion dollars in 1997 and 5.885 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
