<HEADLINE> Uganda's Nomadic Region Given Ultimatum on Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has appealed to Karimojong, a nomadic people in northeastern part
of the country, who have guns in neighboring districts to take
them back to their district or hand them over to the army.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal when addressing a public rally in Katakwi
district in eastern Uganda Tuesday afternoon, a press release from
the President's Office said.
</P>
<P>
Indiscipline of stealing cattle, destroying crops and killing
people in neighboring districts by the Karimojong, is
unacceptable, he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the problem of banditry and cattle rustling
mainly sprang from the weakening of the pillars of state during
past regimes and assured the local people that the government has
managed to rehabilitate and strengthen the pillars of state and is
now ready to contain the Karimojong menace.
</P>
<P>
The government requires the Karimojong to respect the law in as
far as it relates to their neighbors as well as to the communities
within Karamoja itself.
</P>
<P>
According to an order recently communicated to the region, all
the guns should be removed from the neighboring districts within a
period of three weeks from March 12 of 1999.
</P>
<P>
To enforce this, Museveni added, the government will deploy
4,000 soldiers in the areas affected.And a battalion will be
permanently stationed at the boundaries of each affected district.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the government will in the next financial year
create a special mechanized battalion to complement the permanent
infantry troops.
</P>
<P>
The mechanized battalion will have detachments at designated
areas to ensure fast and efficient methods of handling the
Karimojong problem.
</P>
<P>
The Karimojong mounts cattle raids on neighboring communities
particularly the Iteso to the south, Langi and Acholi to the west
and the Pokot Turkana of Kenya to the east.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, they acquired AK 47 and G3 rifles during the time
former President Idi Amin was toppled, when they looted the army
barracks in Moroto District and made off with about 15,000 guns
together with an estimated two million rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
The fleeing soldiers of the Okello government in 1986 meant
additional weaponry. They learned to use the gun through self
training and with the help of the former Karimojong soldiers in
the previous armies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
