<HEADLINE> N.Irish Court Rules early Release of IRA Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A Northern Ireland judge Tuesday
dismissed an application by the British government to delay the
early release of four jailed Irish Republican Army (IRA)
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
British Home Secretary (interior minister) Jack Straw wants the
court to review a decision by the Northern Ireland Sentence Review
Commission allowing early freedom for the men, who are all serving
life sentences.
</P>
<P>
But Judge Paul Girvan said after a six-hour hearing in
Belfast's High Court, "I conclude that the reasoning of the
(panel's) commissioners has not been demonstrated to be legally
flawed."
</P>
<P>
The ruling would allow three of the four IRA prisoners to go
home Tuesday night and the fourth man to be released in June.
</P>
<P>
A lawyer for Straw told Girvan he would consult the home
secretary to determine whether an appeal would be lodged against
the judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred prisoners from the IRA and pro-British
"loyalist" guerrilla groups have been freed early by the review
commission, a body created under the Northern Ireland peace
agreement. All those still behind bars are to be released by July
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
