<HEADLINE> Malian President: Africans Must Find Solution to Issues Themselves  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Malian President Alpha Oumar
Konare Tuesday urged African leaders to help find solutions to the
problems of the continent instead of depending on external
assistance.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody will solve our problems for us or substitute anything.
It is only through regional cooperation that we can harness our
resources for our benefits," he said in Ghana during a visit.
</P>
<P>
Konare was speaking at a pre-departure press conference in
Accra after a one-day visit during which he held talks with his
Ghanaian counterpart Jerry Rawlings, according to the Ghanaian
News Agency (GNA).
</P>
<P>
Konare said it is the responsibility of all African leaders to
pool their resources together to stop conflicts and wars on the
continent so that they can concentrate on economic development.
</P>
<P>
"The African situation is not so fatal that we cannot reverse
it. It is as a result of bad policies which we can no longer
accept."
</P>
<P>
Konare reminded African leaders to rely and cooperate with such
 regional groupings as the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) to promote social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
"We should not allow ourselves to be divided on colonial lines
which often divide us. We must promote values like dialog,
tolerance and reject marginalization for the greater freedom of
our people."
</P>
<P>
Konare assumes the ECOWAS chairmanship soon.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings said there is the need for Africans to have a common
agenda in solving issues affecting the continent.
</P>
<P>
He said the aspirations of the founding fathers to cooperate
and help each other should not be lost but continued.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings said ethnicity should not divide Africans in their
quest for political and economic advancement and urged all
Africans to put in their maximum to move the continent forward.
</P>
<P>
He urged the media in Africa to use constructive criticism to
project the continent's determination to achieve economic
emancipation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
