<HEADLINE> Kenya Names New Anti-corruption Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- President Daniel arap Moi Tuesday
 appointed Justice Aaron Ringera as director of the Kenya
Anti-Corruption Authority (KACA) , paving the way for the
resumption of talks on loans with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
Justice Ringera replaced former director Harun Mwau who was
suspended and became the subject of a tribunal on a charge of
incompetence.
</P>
<P>
A news dispatch from the Presidential Press Service said
Justice Ringera had been recommended by the Advisory Board of the
Kenya Anti-Corruption Authority.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of the KACA director and vice-directors has
been the only remaining obstacle to the re-opening of negotiations
on the resumption of the IMF's 205 million U.S. dollars loan to
Kenya, halted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The IMF announced in early March that Kenya had met other
conditions set by the agency.
</P>
<P>
Before his appointment to the Attorney-General's chambers in
1997, Ringera was a judge in the High Court.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Anti-Corruption Authority Act provides for two
assistant directors whose appointments are staggered so that at
all times, there is a deputy who serves for two years.
</P>
<P>
Before Ringera's appointment, speculation was rife that the
head of the anti-graft body would be an expatriate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
