<DOCNO> XIE19990324.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Hails Libyan Decision to Hand Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Tuesday extended a welcome to the letter from the Libyan foreign
minister to the U.N. Secretary-General, saying that the 15-member
Council "looked forward to the implementation of that handover in
accordance with the agreed arrangements."
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the Security
Council, Qin Huasun of China, said that "Security Council members
welcomed the letter from the Foreign Minister of the Libyan Aran
Jamahiriya to the Secretary-General of May 19, 1999, indicating
that the two suspects would be available for the Secretary-General
to take the custody of them on or before April 6."
</P>
<P>
"Security Council members reaffirmed existing Security Council
resolutions as the basis to bring about a full and final
resolution of the situation," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Security Council members looked forward to the implementation
of that handover in accordance with the agreed arrangements and,
taking into account also the information provided by the French
authorities regarding UTA 772, to the immediate suspension of
sanctions with a view to lifting them as soon as circumstances
permit, in accordance with relevant Security Council resolutions,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Security Council members thanked the Secretary-General for his
tireless efforts in reaching an understanding with the Libyan Arab
Jamahiriya on the implementation of Security Council resolution
1192 (1998), and expressed appreciation also for the positive
actions taken by the Governments of South Africa, Saudi Arabia and
other countries in support of these efforts," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
On Friday afternoon, the Libyan permanent representative to the
United Nations, Abuzed Omar Dorda, hand delivered to the U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan a letter from Omar Mustafa Muntasser,
the Libyan foreign minister, confirming the readiness of Libya to
proceed with the transfer of the two accused to the trial before a
Scottish court sitting in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is greatly encouraged by this
development and the necessary arrangements will now be initiated
by the Secretariat," a Friday statement, issued by the U.N.
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, together with Saudi Arabia, has been at the heart
of the efforts to achieve the breakthrough in solving the
long-standing of the bombing of a Pan Am airliner over the
Scottish town of Lockerbie in December 1988, killing 270 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
