<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, March 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has
helped Israel thwart a serious terrorist attack, the local daily
Yediot Aharonot disclosed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted Israeli security sources as saying the PNA
transferred information on the terrorist attack, which might cause
a large casualties, to Israel about three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu also has telephoned
the PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat to express his thanks for the
information. (BC-Palestine-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides confirmed on
Monday night there are plans for another defense system to meet
Cyprus' security needs, the local media reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on the occasion of the
completion of the first year of his second term in office, he also
said even though the Russian missiles were eventually diverted to
Greece, the Cyprus government still believes an anti-aircraft
weapons system is needed to protect the Paphos air base.
(BC-Cyprus-Missiles)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The death toll in Monday's lorry plunge rose to 30
Tuesday after four more died in hospitals in Iran's southwestern
province of Khuzestan.
</P>
<P>
A lorry carrying 60 people, aged between 12 and 15 years, fell
into a valley on the mountainous road Shahyoun in Sardasht
district of Dezful, killing 26 instantly.
</P>
<P>
It was returning from a Koran recitation session when the
incident occurred, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
Some injured are still in a critical condition, it added.
(BC-Iran-Accident-Death Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Hundreds of Beduin fleeing into Israel from the
Sinai desert earlier this month were deported back to Egypt
Tuesday, two days after the High Court of Justice rejected their
request to stay in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The deportation also came after Egypt has promised to protect
the safety of the 800 Beduin, who crossed the Israeli-Egyptian
border on March 15 to escape a tribal feud, Israel Radio said.
(BC-Israel-Beduin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OAPEC) expects that world demand for oil is likely to
reach 75 million barrels per day (bpd) in 1999, compared with 74
million bpd in 1998.
</P>
<P>
While the second quarter of this year will see a 2.7 million
bpd drop in world demand from 75.7 million bpd in the first
quarter, the rest two quarters will witness a rise, the
Kuwait-based OAPEC said in its latest issue of monthly newsletter
for March. (BC-Kuwait-OAPEC-Oil) 
</P>
</TEXT>
