<HEADLINE> UK Inflation Beats Government's Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON March 23 (Xinhua) - The UK's inflation rate has dropped
below the government's target of 2.5 percent to its lowest level
in more than four years.
</P>
<P>
The annual underlying rate of inflation has fallen to 2.4
percent in February, according to official figures released by the
Office for National Statistics Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The headline rate in inflation - which includes mortgage costs
- has fallen to its lowest level since December 1993.
</P>
<P>
The figures provide further evidence that the UK economy is
slowing down sharply and boost hopes that interest rates will be
cut again next month.
</P>
<P>
The fall in underlying inflation was given the full seal of
approval by the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Gordon Brown.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Commons Treasury Select Committee, Brown said:
"I think today's announcement of 2.4 percent inflation....shows
that over the years we will meet our inflation target and are
continuing to steer a course of stability in a difficult and
troubled world."
</P>
<P>
The inflation news sparked a brief flurry of buying in London
Stock market, as economists said there was now no reason why the
Monetary Policy Committee wouldn't resume their rate cutting
agenda at the next meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, London shares spent the day in the red, barely lifted
by the inflation news and hit late by a sharp sell-off on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index ended 92 points down at 6060, a loss of 1.5
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
