<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Close Deep in Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON March 23 (Xinhua) - Europe's main stock markets beat a
retreat throughout Tuesday, with all the bourses closing deep in
the red.
</P>
<P>
London shares spent the day in the red, barely lifted by
positive inflation figures and hit late by a sharp sell-off on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE-100 Index of leading shares closed down 92.3 points at
6060.5 - not far off its lowest point of the day which was down
104 points.
</P>
<P>
Hopes of further cuts in interest rates were prompted by
official data showing inflation in February undershot the
government's 2.5 percent target.
</P>
<P>
But this paled into insignificance as the Dow Jones Industrial
Average nosedived more than 150 points, leaving prospects for
another breach of the 10000 barrier looking unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
Germany's electronically-traded Xetra Dax led the decline,
sinking 3.26 percent to 4870.49, a drop of 164 points, after it
had passed through the psychologically- important 5000 mark in the
morning session.
</P>
<P>
Most of the gains created by the euphoria over the shock
resignation of left-leaning finance minister Oskar Lafontaine
almost two weeks ago now have evaporated.
</P>
<P>
Paris wasn't far behind, with the CAC 40 index losing 2.8
percent, or 117 points, to close at 4079.47. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
