<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Vows to Support U.N. Mission in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Tuesday stressed their support for the United Nations Mission in
Bosnia and Herzegovina (UNMIBH) and called upon the leaders of
both entities to honor the Dayton Peace Agreement.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the
15-member council, Qin Huasun of China, said, "Council members
reaffirmed their support for the UNMIBH in fulfilling its mandate
in police monitoring, restructuring and reform, in assessment of
the judicial system and in strengthening the legal system's
respect for human rights."
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the Security Council discussed the
report of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the UNMIBH.
</P>
<P>
"Members welcomed the progress in police restructuring and
reform, as well as in the establishment of the rule of law in both
entities," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"They appealed to both entities to commit themselves to further
progress in order to make it self-sustaining," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Aware of the recent challenges to the political stability of
Bosnia and Herzegovina, the members reminded the leaders of both
entities of their obligation to fulfill the provisions of the
Dayton Peace Agreement and appealed for an effort to ensure the
functioning of common institutions in the country," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Annan presented his report on the situation in
Bosnia and Herzegovina, saying that "the establishment of the rule
of law is a prerequisite for a lasting peace in Bosnia and
Herzegovina."
</P>
<P>
"The rule of law provides an essential safeguard for individual
rights regardless of ethnicity, it gives investors confidence in
the country's future, and it facilitates increasingly close
association between European institutions and those of Bosnia and
Herzegovina," he said.
</P>
<P>
The UNMIBH "continues to play a central role in efforts to that
end under its mandate in police monitoring, restructuring and
reform, assessment of the judicial system and strengthening of the
legal system's respect for human rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The UNMIBH has pursued a strategy of engaging senior officials
in the Republika Srpska and the Federation, through co-location of
the International Police Task Force (IPTF) advisers and launching
a series of inter-entity meetings between officials from the
ministries of the interior," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This strategy of engagement has enjoyed some success in both
entities," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Despite all efforts, it is not clear whether these positive
steps will mark the beginning of self-sustaining progress in
police in police restructuring and reform and the establishment of
the rule of law," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Monitoring, therefore, remains the central to the work of the
IPTF because it enables the mission to identify areas where the
IPTF must focus its programs of training, advising and equipping,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Further progress in the mission's central task of police
reform will require tangible material support for the
modernization of the country's police infrastructure from a donor
community whose support for police restructuring and reform has
until now been relatively modest," he added.
</P>
<P>
The UNMIBH is headed by Elisabeth Rehn of Finland, the
secretary-general's special representative and coordinator of
United Nations operations in Bosnia and Herzegovina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
