<HEADLINE> Light Sentence of Baby Killer Sparks Anger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The black community in
Delmas near Johannesburg was angered Tuesday after a white man was
given a suspended sentence for killing a six-month-old baby.
</P>
<P>
Shouts of "One settler, one bullet" and "Kill the boer, kill
the farmer" rang out outside the Delmas Circuit Court after the
court ruling was handed down, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Steyn left the court in effect a free man with a
five-year jail term suspended for three years. But he had to be
protected by police and soldiers from an angry crowd who bayed for
his blood.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers used their rifles to keep protesters away from the
driveway of the magistrate's court and members of the crowd struck
the armored police car carrying Steyn with sticks as it drove away
from the court.
</P>
<P>
The victim's family accused the presiding judge, Tjibbe
Spoelstra, of racism.
</P>
<P>
Angelina Zwane's parents were visibly upset, with her father
Isaac Zwane openly crying during interviews with journalists.
</P>
<P>
Relative David Dlamini said: "If it was a black man who killed
a white person, he would have received about 50 years."
</P>
<P>
Steyn was convicted on March 4 of culpable homicide and assault
for firing the shot that killed Angelina.
</P>
<P>
Steyn shot Angelina while she was being carried on the back of
her 11- year-old cousin, Francina Dlamini, across his property
near Benoni. Dlamini was also struck by the bullet.
</P>
<P>
The judge found that her death was "a tragic accident" as Steyn
had not aimed at the children and had no intention of hurting
them.
</P>
<P>
Forensic evidence presented in court showed Steyn had fired
upward, well above the children, but that the bullet had hit an
overhead electric cable and ricocheted down toward them.
</P>
<P>
Omar, however, appeared to challenge the judgement later
Tuesday, saying he was sure the public was shocked by the mild
sentence.
</P>
<P>
Omar said he would ask for a report on the case from the
director of public prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure the imposition of a suspended sentence caused shock
and unhappiness in the minds of the members of the family, the
community and many others," Omar said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that Steyn was found guilty of culpable
homicide and not murder had also shocked the baby's family.
</P>
<P>
"Whilst I cannot comment on the findings and sentence given by
the court, I want to point out the government views all killings
in a very serious light and we expect our courts to give decisions
and impose sentences which are fair and engender a respect for the
courts," he said.
</P>
<P>
The African National Congress in Gauteng said it would proceed
with a civil case against Steyn.
</P>
<P>
Freedom Front leader Constand Viljoen said the sentence was an
indication that South Africa's justice system was still
functioning. He said considering the facts, the sentence was fair
and would contribute to restoring the faith among farmers in the
country's courts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
