<HEADLINE> Nigerian Military Urged to Ensure Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalami Abubakar Tuesday said that the country would be better
served if the military can return to their constitutional duties
of protecting the territorial integrity of the country.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day workshop to re-orientate the military and
police for their post-military role, he noted: "we must allow
democracy to take root in our country, if we do not, we will
continue to be isolated in the world."
</P>
<P>
Abubakar who is scheduled to hand over power to President-Elect
Olusegun Obasanjo on May 29, noted that the military has ruled the
country for 29 of the 39 years since its independence in 1960 and
has been blamed for frustrating efforts at democratization in
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He absolved the military from full responsibility for
undermining efforts at democratization in the west African
country, saying that "politicians have been known to invite the
military to take over in order to settle scores."
</P>
<P>
At the workshop organized by the Defense Headquarters in
capital Abuja, Chief of Defense Staff Air Marshal Al-Amin Daggash
said it would be difficult to insulate the military immediately
from politics after years of incursion.
</P>
<P>
He added that a generation of the officers, especially those
below the rank of colonel, were not familiar with any other form
of governance.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the workshop was designed to re-orientate and
 sensitize members of the armed forces and the police on their
constitutional role as the country transcends into civil rule on
May 29.
</P>
<P>
Daggash said that the workshop would also re-orient the
military to subordinate themselves to civil authority and would
brain-storm on the ways and means to ensure an "enduring and
lasting democracy in the most populous African country.  Light
Sentence of Baby Killer Sparks Anger s well as the media and the
general public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
