<HEADLINE> Sudanese Envoy Suggests Talks on Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Ambassador to Kenya,
Farouk Ali Mohammed, said Tuesday a ministerial commission would
be convened between Kenya and Sudan to resolve the refugee
problem.
</P>
<P>
The envoy, who had called on Kenyan Minister for Home Affairs
Shariff Nassir, said the best solution would be to repatriate the
refugees under the auspices of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Nassir said his ministry was concerned about refugees and
requested the Sudanese government to ensure that those refugees
who had come earlier were repatriated before the new ones.
</P>
<P>
He said refugees could not be blamed "since leaders are the
ones who destroy a country". He hoped the civil war in Sudan
would be resolved soon.
</P>
<P>
Nassir urged the east African countries to meet and resolve
the regional problems.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed hoped the rebel John Garang faction would come to the
peace talks scheduled for the end of April in Nairobi and said
that donors were likely to freeze aid to Sudan if the talks
failed.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed said his government advocated unity between northern
and southern Sudan rather than secession, although autonomy for
southern Sudan was not ruled out.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador denied claims of slavery in Sudan and termed it
as a slanderous campaign mounted by people who conceived his
government as fundamentalist and harboring terrorists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
